# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pl-i-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran was originally developed by IBM with a reference manual being released in 1956; however, the first compilers only began to produce accurate code two years later.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran computer programs have been written to support scientific and engineering applications, such as numerical weather prediction, finite element analysis, computational fluid dynamics, plasma physics, geophysics, computational physics, crystallography and computational chemistry.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It is a popular language for high-performance computing and is used for programs that benchmark and rank the world's fastest supercomputers.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran has evolved through numerous versions and dialects.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The two most important early versions were FORTRAN II and FORTRAN IV.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] In 1966, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) developed a standard for Fortran to limit proliferation of compilers using slightly different syntax.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Successive versions have added support for a character data type, structured programming (Fortran 77), array programming, modular programming, generic programming (Fortran 90), parallel computing (Fortran 95), object-oriented programming (Fortran 2003), and concurrent programming (Fortran 2008).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The first manual for FORTRAN describes it as a *Formula Translating System*, and printed the name with small caps, Fortran.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Other sources suggest the name stands for *Formula Translator*, or, most commonly, *Formula Translation*.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Early IBM computers did not support lowercase letters, and the names of versions of the language through FORTRAN 77 were usually spelled in all-uppercase.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] FORTRAN 77 was the last version in which the Fortran character set included only uppercase letters.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The Fortran 90 standard changed the language name from "FORTRAN" with all-caps to "Fortran" with initial caps.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Backus submitted a proposal to his superiors at IBM to develop a more practical alternative to assembly language for programming their IBM 704 mainframe computer.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Backus' historic FORTRAN team consisted of programmers Richard Goldberg, Sheldon F.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Best, Harlan Herrick, Peter Sheridan, Roy Nutt, Robert Nelson, Irving Ziller, Harold Stern, Lois Haibt, and David Sayre.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Its concepts included easier entry of equations into a computer, an idea developed by J.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Halcombe Laning and demonstrated in the Laning and Zierler system of 1952.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A draft specification for *The IBM Mathematical Formula Translating System* was completed by November 1954.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The first manual for FORTRAN appeared in October 1956, with the first FORTRAN compiler delivered in April 1957.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran produced efficient enough code for assembly language programmers to accept a high-level programming language replacement.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] John Backus said during a 1979 interview with *Think*, the IBM employee magazine, "Much of my work has come from being lazy.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The language was widely adopted by scientists for writing numerically intensive programs, which encouraged compiler writers to produce compilers that could generate faster and more efficient code.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The inclusion of a complex number data type in the language made Fortran especially suited to technical applications such as electrical engineering.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] By 1960, versions of FORTRAN were available for the IBM 709, 650, 1620, and 7090 computers.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Significantly, the increasing popularity of FORTRAN spurred competing computer manufacturers to provide FORTRAN compilers for their machines, so that by 1963 over 40 FORTRAN compilers existed.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] So pervasive was the language within the computing industry that by that time, over 220,000 Fortran manuals of all kinds had been distributed.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] FORTRAN was provided for the IBM 1401 computer by an innovative 63-phase compiler that ran entirely in its core memory of only 8000 (six-bit) characters.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The compiler could be run from tape, or from a 2200-card deck; it used no further tape or disk storage.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It kept the program in memory and loaded overlays that gradually transformed it, in place, into executable form, as described by Haines.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This article was reprinted, edited, in both editions of *Anatomy of a Compiler* and in the IBM manual "Fortran Specifications and Operating Procedures, IBM 1401".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The executable form was not entirely machine language; rather, floating-point arithmetic, sub-scripting, input/output, and function references were interpreted, preceding UCSD Pascal P-code by two decades.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] GOTRAN, a simplified, interpreted version of FORTRAN I (with only 12 types of statements not 32) for "load and go" operation was available (at least for the early IBM 1620 computer).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Modern Fortran, and almost all later versions, are fully compiled, as done for other high-performance languages.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The development of Fortran paralleled the early evolution of compiler technology, and many advances in the theory and design of compilers were specifically motivated by the need to generate efficient code for Fortran programs.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Indeed, the Fortran compiler was one of the most complicated programs of any kind in existence at the time, and it was used by IBM's Product Test group in Poughkeepsie, New York, as part of acceptance testing for newly built computers.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The arithmetic `IF` statement was reminiscent of (but not readily implementable by) a three-way comparison instruction (CAS—Compare Accumulator with Storage) available on the 704.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The statement provided the only way to compare numbers—by testing their difference, with an attendant risk of overflow.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This deficiency was later overcome by "logical" facilities introduced in FORTRAN IV.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The `FREQUENCY` statement was used originally (and optionally) to give branch probabilities for the three branch cases of the arithmetic `IF` statement.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It could also be used to suggest how many iterations a `DO` loop might run.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The first FORTRAN compiler used this weighting to perform *at compile time* a Monte Carlo simulation of the generated code, the results of which were used to optimize the placement of basic blocks in memory—a very sophisticated optimization for its time.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The first FORTRAN compiler reported diagnostic information by halting the program when an error was found and outputting an error code on its console.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] That code could be looked up by the programmer in an error messages table in the operator's manual, providing them with a brief description of the problem.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Later, an error-handling subroutine to handle user errors such as division by zero, developed by NASA, was incorporated, informing users of which line of code contained the error.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Before the development of disk files, text editors and terminals, programs were most often entered on a keypunch keyboard onto 80-column punched cards, one line to a card.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The resulting deck of cards would be fed into a card reader to be compiled.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Punched card codes included no lower-case letters or many special characters, and special versions of the IBM 026 keypunch were offered that would correctly print the re-purposed special characters used in FORTRAN.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Reflecting punched card input practice, Fortran programs were originally written in a fixed-column format.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A letter "C" in column 1 caused the entire card to be treated as a comment and ignored by the compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Columns 73 to 80 could therefore be used for identification information, such as punching a sequence number or text, which could be used to re-order cards if a stack of cards was dropped; though in practice this was reserved for stable, production programs.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] An IBM 519 could be used to copy a program deck and add sequence numbers.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Some early compilers, e.g., the IBM 650's, had additional restrictions due to limitations on their card readers.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Keypunches could be programmed to tab to column 7 and skip out after column 72.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Later compilers relaxed most fixed-format restrictions, and the requirement was eliminated in the Fortran 90 standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Within the statement field, whitespace characters (blanks) were ignored outside a text literal.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This allowed omitting spaces between tokens for brevity or including spaces within identifiers for clarity.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Note the slight visual difference between a comma and a period.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Hollerith strings, originally allowed only in FORMAT and DATA statements, were prefixed by a character count and the letter H (e.g., `26HTHIS IS ALPHANUMERIC DATA.`), allowing blanks to be retained within the character string.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The main enhancement was to support procedural programming by allowing user-written subroutines and functions which returned values with parameters passed by reference.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The COMMON statement provided a way for subroutines to access common (or global) variables.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Over the next few years, FORTRAN II added support for the `DOUBLE PRECISION` and `COMPLEX` data types.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Early FORTRAN compilers supported no recursion in subroutines.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The lack of recursion was a significant detriment to the language being used in conjunction with certain algorithms and applications, and indeed limited how programmers could think about such things.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Although not specified in FORTRAN 77, many F77 compilers supported recursion as an option, and the Burroughs mainframes, designed with recursion built-in, did so by default.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It became a standard in Fortran 90 via the new keyword RECURSIVE.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This program, for Heron's formula, reads data on a tape reel containing three 5-digit integers A, B, and C as input.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] There are no "type" declarations available: variables whose name starts with I, J, K, L, M, or N are "fixed-point" (i.e. integers), otherwise floating-point.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Since integers are to be processed in this example, the names of the variables start with the letter "I".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The name of a variable must start with a letter and can continue with both letters and digits, up to a limit of six characters in FORTRAN II.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] If A, B, and C cannot represent the sides of a triangle in plane geometry, then the program's execution will end with an error code of "STOP 1".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] IBM also developed a *FORTRAN III* in 1958 that allowed for inline assembly code among other features; however, this version was never released as a product.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Like the 704 FORTRAN and FORTRAN II, FORTRAN III included machine-dependent features that made code written in it unportable from machine to machine, as well as Boolean expression support.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Early versions of FORTRAN provided by other vendors suffered from the same disadvantage.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] IBM began development of **FORTRAN IV** in 1961 as a result of customer demands.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] FORTRAN IV was eventually released in 1962, first for the IBM 7030 ("Stretch") computer, followed by versions for the IBM 7090/7094 in 1963 and later for the IBM 1401 in 1966.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] By 1965, FORTRAN IV was supposed to be compliant with the *standard* being developed by the American Standards Association X3.4.3 FORTRAN Working Group.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Between 1966 and 1968, IBM offered several FORTRAN IV compilers for its System/360, each named by letters that indicated the minimum amount of memory the compiler needed to run.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] In particular, the FORTRAN H compiler played an important role in the development of certain kinds of optimization approaches, such as allocating a specific set of registers to hold the values of variables while in a loop.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Overall, the compiler had three levels of possible optimization, as Fortran compiler developers had learned early on that the ability to turn off optimization was a necessity, since it drove up compilation times considerability for program runs that often were not going to work anyway.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Even with the larger amount of main memory available to it, the FORTRAN H compiler was still organized via a number of overlays.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Overall, Fortran compilers were a significant source of revenue for IBM, with sales of some $300 million in 1966 (equivalent to $2,977 million in 2025).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Digital Equipment Corporation maintained DECSYSTEM-10 Fortran IV (F40) for PDP-10 from 1967 to 1975.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Compilers were also available for the UNIVAC 1100 series and the Control Data 6000 series and 7000 series systems.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] In the FORTRAN IV programming environment of the era, except for that used on Control Data Corporation (CDC) systems, only one instruction was placed per line.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The CDC version allowed for multiple instructions per line if separated by a $ (dollar) character.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The FORTRAN sheet was divided into four fields, as described above.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Two compilers of the time, IBM "G" and UNIVAC, allowed comments to be written on the same line as instructions, separated by a special character: "master space": V (perforations 7 and 8) for UNIVAC and perforations 12/11/0/7/8/9 (hexadecimal FF) for IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] These comments were not to be inserted in the middle of continuation cards.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The resulting two standards, approved in March 1966, defined two languages, *FORTRAN* (based on FORTRAN IV, which had served as a de facto standard), and *Basic FORTRAN* (based on FORTRAN II, but stripped of its machine-dependent features).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The FORTRAN defined by the first standard, officially denoted X3.9-1966, became known as *FORTRAN 66* (although many continued to term it FORTRAN IV, the language on which the standard was largely based).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] FORTRAN 66 effectively became the first industry-standard version of FORTRAN.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The above Fortran II version of the Heron program needs several modifications to compile as a Fortran 66 program.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Modifications include using the more machine independent versions of the `READ` and `WRITE` statements, and removal of the unneeded `FLOATF` type conversion functions.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Though not required, the arithmetic `IF` statements can be re-written to use logical `IF` statements and expressions in a more structured fashion.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Although ill-suited for most military-related applications, Fortran was nonetheless one of only a few high-level languages approved for use by the U.S.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Final drafts of this revised standard circulated in 1977, leading to formal approval of the new FORTRAN standard in April 1978.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] In this revision of the standard, a number of features were removed or altered in a manner that might invalidate formerly standard-conforming programs.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A Fortran 77 version of the Heron program requires no modifications to the Fortran 66 version.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] However this example demonstrates additional cleanup of the I/O statements, including using list-directed I/O, and replacing the Hollerith edit descriptors in the `FORMAT` statements with quoted strings.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It also uses structured `IF` and `END IF` statements, rather than `GOTO`/`CONTINUE`.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The development of a revised standard to succeed FORTRAN 77 would be repeatedly delayed as the standardization process struggled to keep up with rapid changes in computing and programming practice.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] In the meantime, as the "Standard FORTRAN" for nearly fifteen years, FORTRAN 77 would become the historically most important dialect.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] An important practical extension to FORTRAN 77 was the release of MIL-STD-1753 in 1978.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This specification, developed by the U.S.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Department of Defense, standardized a number of features implemented by most FORTRAN 77 compilers but not included in the ANSI FORTRAN 77 standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] These features would eventually be incorporated into the Fortran 90 standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The IEEE 1003.9 POSIX Standard, released in 1991, provided a simple means for FORTRAN 77 programmers to issue POSIX system calls.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Over 100 calls were defined in the document – allowing access to POSIX-compatible process control, signal handling, file system control, device control, procedure pointing, and stream I/O in a portable manner.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The much-delayed successor to FORTRAN 77, informally known as *Fortran 90* (and prior to that, *Fortran 8X*), was finally released as ISO/IEC standard 1539:1991 in 1991 and an ANSI Standard in 1992.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Unlike the prior revision, Fortran 90 removed no features.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Any standard-conforming FORTRAN 77 program was also standard-conforming under Fortran 90, and either standard should have been usable to define its behavior.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A small set of features were identified as "obsolescent" and were expected to be removed in a future standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] All of the functionalities of these early-version features can be performed by newer Fortran features.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Some are kept to simplify porting of old programs but many were deleted in Fortran 95.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A number of intrinsic functions were extended (for example a `dim` argument was added to the `maxloc` intrinsic).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] An important supplement to Fortran 95 was the ISO technical report *TR-15581: Enhanced Data Type Facilities*, informally known as the *Allocatable TR.* This specification defined enhanced use of `ALLOCATABLE` arrays, prior to the availability of fully Fortran 2003-compliant Fortran compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Such uses include `ALLOCATABLE` arrays as derived type components, in procedure dummy argument lists, and as function return values.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] (`ALLOCATABLE` arrays are preferable to `POINTER`-based arrays because `ALLOCATABLE` arrays are guaranteed by Fortran 95 to be deallocated automatically when they go out of scope, eliminating the possibility of memory leakage.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Another important supplement to Fortran 95 was the ISO technical report *TR-15580: Floating-point exception handling*, informally known as the *IEEE TR.* This specification defined support for IEEE floating-point arithmetic and floating-point exception handling.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] which, together, compose the multi-part International Standard (ISO/IEC 1539).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The language defined by the twenty-first century standards, in particular because of its incorporation of object-oriented programming support and subsequently Coarray Fortran, is often referred to as 'Modern Fortran', and the term is increasingly used in the literature.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] An important supplement to Fortran 2003 was the ISO technical report *TR-19767: Enhanced module facilities in Fortran.* This report provided *sub-modules,* which make Fortran modules more similar to Modula-2 modules.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] They are similar to Ada private child sub-units.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This allows the specification and implementation of a module to be expressed in separate program units, which improves packaging of large libraries, allows preservation of trade secrets while publishing definitive interfaces, and prevents compilation cascades.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] ISO/IEC 1539-1:2010, informally known as Fortran 2008, was approved in September 2010.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] As with Fortran 95, this is a minor upgrade, incorporating clarifications and corrections to Fortran 2003, as well as introducing some new capabilities.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The Final Draft international Standard (FDIS) is available as document N1830.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A supplement to Fortran 2008 is the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) Technical Specification (TS) 29113 on *Further Interoperability of Fortran with C*, which has been submitted to ISO in May 2012 for approval.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The specification adds support for accessing the array descriptor from C and allows ignoring the type and rank of arguments.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The Fortran 2018 revision of the language was earlier referred to as Fortran 2015.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It was a significant revision and was released on November 28, 2018.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Additional changes and new features include support for ISO/IEC/IEEE 60559:2011 (the version of the IEEE floating-point standard before the latest minor revision IEEE 754–2019), hexadecimal input/output, IMPLICIT NONE enhancements and other changes.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran 2018 deleted the arithmetic IF statement.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It also deleted non-block DO constructs - loops which do not end with an END DO or CONTINUE statement.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] These had been an obsolescent part of the language since Fortran 90.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] New obsolescences are: COMMON and EQUIVALENCE statements and the BLOCK DATA program unit, labelled DO loops, specific names for intrinsic functions, and the FORALL statement and construct.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran 2023 (ISO/IEC 1539-1:2023) was published in November 2023, and can be purchased from the ISO.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Fortran 2023 is a minor extension of Fortran 2018 that focuses on correcting errors and omissions in Fortran 2018.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It also adds several small features, including conditional expressions and arguments, simple procedures, and an enumerated type capability.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Degree- and half revolution based trig functions were also added.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Degree-based trig functions were previously a very common vendor extension.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] A full description of the Fortran language features brought by Fortran 95 is covered in the related article, *Fortran 95 language features*.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The language versions defined by later standards are often referred to collectively as 'Modern Fortran' and are described in the literature.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Although a 1968 journal article by the authors of BASIC already described FORTRAN as "old-fashioned", programs have been written in Fortran for many decades and there is a vast body of Fortran software in daily use throughout the scientific and engineering communities.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Jay Pasachoff wrote in 1984 that "physics and astronomy students simply have to learn FORTRAN.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] So much exists in FORTRAN that it seems unlikely that scientists will change to Pascal, Modula-2, or whatever." In 1993, Cecil E.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Leith called FORTRAN the "mother tongue of scientific computing", adding that its replacement by any other possible language "may remain a forlorn hope".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Many of the floating-point benchmarks to gauge the performance of new computer processors, such as the floating-point components of the SPEC benchmarks (e.g., CFP2006, CFP2017) are written in Fortran.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Math algorithms are well documented in Numerical Recipes.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Apart from this, more modern codes in computational science generally use large program libraries, such as METIS for graph partitioning, PETSc or Trilinos for linear algebra capabilities, deal.II or FEniCS for mesh and finite element support, and other generic libraries.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Since the early 2000s, many of the widely used support libraries have also been implemented in C and more recently, in C++.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] On the other hand, high-level languages such as the Wolfram Language, MATLAB, Python, and R have become popular in particular areas of computational science.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Consequently, a growing fraction of scientific programs are also written in such higher-level scripting languages.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] For this reason, facilities for inter-operation with C were added to Fortran 2003 and enhanced by the ISO/IEC technical specification 29113, which was incorporated into Fortran 2018 to allow more flexible interoperation with other programming languages.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Portability was a problem in the early days because there was no agreed upon standard—not even IBM's reference manual—and computer companies vied to differentiate their offerings from others by providing incompatible features.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The 1966 standard provided a reference syntax and semantics, but vendors continued to provide incompatible extensions.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Government were required to diagnose extensions of the standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Rather than offer two processors, essentially every compiler eventually had at least an option to diagnose extensions.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Incompatible extensions were not the only portability problem.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] For numerical calculations, it is important to take account of the characteristics of the arithmetic.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This was addressed by Fox et al. in the context of the 1966 standard by the *PORT* library.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The ideas therein became widely used, and were eventually incorporated into the 1990 standard by way of intrinsic inquiry functions.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] The widespread (now almost universal) adoption of the IEEE 754 standard for binary floating-point arithmetic has essentially removed this problem.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Access to the computing environment (e.g., the program's command line, environment variables, textual explanation of error conditions) remained a problem until it was addressed by the 2003 standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] Large collections of library software that could be described as being loosely related to engineering and scientific calculations, such as graphics libraries, have been written in C, and therefore access to them presented a portability problem.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] This has been addressed by incorporation of C interoperability into the 2003 standard.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p01] It is now possible (and relatively easy) to write an entirely portable program in Fortran, even without recourse to a preprocessor.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Until the Fortran 66 standard was developed, each compiler supported its own variant of Fortran.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Some were more divergent from the mainstream than others.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] One of the most prominent textbooks of the time, Daniel D.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] McCracken's *A Guide to FORTRAN IV Programming* (1965), devoted a full two-page matrix of 24 feature differences versus 29 manufacturer-and-computer versions.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Another textbook author from that era, John M.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Univac also offered a compiler for the 1100 series known as FORTRAN V.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] A spinoff of Univac Fortran V was Athena FORTRAN.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] For example, one of IBM's FORTRAN compilers (*H Extended IUP*) had a level of optimization which reordered the machine code instructions to keep multiple internal arithmetic units busy simultaneously.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Another example is *CFD*, a special variant of FORTRAN designed specifically for the ILLIAC IV supercomputer, running at NASA's Ames Research Center.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] IBM Research Labs also developed an extended FORTRAN-based language called *VECTRAN* for processing vectors and matrices.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Such machine-specific extensions have either disappeared over time or have had elements incorporated into the main standards.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The major remaining extension is OpenMP, which is a cross-platform extension for shared memory programming.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] One new extension, Coarray Fortran, is intended to support parallel programming.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Up to ten subroutines could be used in one program.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] FOR TRANSIT statements were limited to columns 7 through 56, only.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Punched cards were used for input and output on the IBM 650.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Two versions existed for the 650s with a 2000 word memory drum: FOR TRANSIT I (S) and FOR TRANSIT II, the latter for machines equipped with indexing registers and automatic floating-point decimal (bi-quinary) arithmetic.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Appendix A of the manual included wiring diagrams for the IBM 533 card reader/punch control panel.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The first FORTRAN compiler set a high standard of efficiency for compiled code.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This goal made it difficult to create a compiler so it was usually done by the computer manufacturers to support hardware sales.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The requirement for execution efficiency remained the primary design criteria for the language through the early evolution of the language.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This left an important niche: compilers that were fast in the compilation and loading phase and provided good diagnostics for the programmer, who was often a student as by this time FORTRAN IV had started to become an important educational tool.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] WATFOR, introduced in the 1960s, was popularly used in colleges and universities.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Developed, supported, and distributed by the University of Waterloo, WATFOR was based largely on FORTRAN IV.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] A student using WATFOR could submit their batch FORTRAN job and, if there were no syntax errors, the program would move straight to execution.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This simplification allowed students to concentrate on their program's syntax and semantics, or execution logic flow, rather than dealing with submission Job Control Language (JCL), the compile/link-edit/execution successive process(es), or other complexities of a mainframe environment.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Moreover, WATFOR presented a superset of the Fortran language, in particular providing so-called "free" `READ` and `PRINT` commands as an alternative to the formatted `READ` and `WRITE>` statements of regular Fortran.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The `FORMAT` statements of the latter allowed considerable flexibility but could be quite complicated, and were sometimes subject to manufacturer differences or site-specific guidelines.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Since the formatted approach caused even experienced programmers difficulties, providing an alternative in a student compiler was a definite advantage.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] A down side to this simplified environment was that WATFOR was not a good choice for programmers needing the expanded abilities of their host processor(s), e.g., WATFOR typically had very limited access to I/O devices.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] WATFOR was succeeded by WATFIV and later versions.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Another student compiler was PUFFT, and on a smaller scale, FORGO, Wits Fortran, and Kingston Fortran 2.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Prior to FORTRAN 77, many preprocessors were commonly used to provide a friendlier language, with the advantage that the preprocessed code could be compiled on any machine with a standard FORTRAN compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] These preprocessors would typically support structured programming, variable names longer than six characters, additional data types, conditional compilation, and even macro capabilities.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Popular preprocessors included EFL, FLECS, iftran, MORTRAN, SFtran, S-Fortran, Ratfor, and Ratfiv.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] EFL, Ratfor and Ratfiv, for example, implemented C-like languages, outputting preprocessed code in standard FORTRAN 66.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The PFORT preprocessor was often used to verify that code conformed to a portable subset of the language.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Despite advances in the Fortran language, preprocessors continue to be used for conditional compilation and macro substitution.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] LRLTRAN was developed at the Lawrence Radiation Laboratory to provide support for vector arithmetic and dynamic storage, among other extensions to support systems programming.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The distribution included the Livermore Time Sharing System (LTSS) operating system.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The Fortran-95 Standard includes an optional *Part 3* which defines an optional conditional compilation capability.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This capability is often referred to as "CoCo".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Many Fortran compilers have integrated subsets of the C preprocessor into their systems.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] SIMSCRIPT is an application specific Fortran preprocessor for modeling and simulating large discrete systems.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The F programming language was designed to be a clean subset of Fortran 95 that attempted to remove the redundant, unstructured, and deprecated features of Fortran, such as the `EQUIVALENCE` statement.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] F retains the array features added in Fortran 90, and removes control statements that were made obsolete by structured programming constructs added to both FORTRAN 77 and Fortran 90.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] F is described by its creators as "a compiled, structured, array programming language especially well suited to education and scientific computing".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Essential Lahey Fortran 90 (ELF90) was a similar subset.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Lahey and Fujitsu teamed up to create Fortran for the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Silverfrost FTN95 is also capable of creating .NET code.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] The following program demonstrates dynamic memory allocation and array-based operations, two features introduced with Fortran 90.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Particularly noteworthy is the absence of `DO` loops and `IF`/`THEN` statements in manipulating the array; mathematical operations are applied to the array as a whole.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Also apparent is the use of descriptive variable names and general code formatting that conform with contemporary programming style.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This example computes an average over data entered interactively.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] During the same FORTRAN standards committee meeting at which the name "FORTRAN 77" was chosen, a satirical technical proposal was incorporated into the official distribution bearing the title "Letter O Considered Harmful".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This proposal purported to address the confusion that sometimes arises between the letter "O" and the numeral zero, by eliminating the letter from allowable variable names.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] However, the method proposed was to eliminate the letter from the character set entirely (thereby retaining 48 as the number of lexical characters, which the colon had increased to 49).
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] This was considered beneficial in that it would promote structured programming, by making it impossible to use the notorious `GO TO` statement as before.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] (Troublesome `FORMAT` statements would also be eliminated.) It was noted that this "might invalidate some existing programs" but that most of these "probably were non-conforming, anyway".
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] When X3J3 debated whether the minimum trip count for a DO loop should be zero or one in Fortran 77, Loren Meissner suggested a minimum trip count of two—reasoning *(tongue-in-cheek)* that if it were less than two, then there would be no reason for a loop.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] When assumed-length arrays were being added, there was a dispute as to the appropriate character to separate upper and lower bounds.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] In a comment examining these arguments, Walt Brainerd penned an article entitled "Astronomy vs.
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Gastroenterology" because some proponents had suggested using the star or asterisk ("*"), while others favored the colon (":").
[src:pl-i-language/fortran-p02] Variable names beginning with the letters I–N have a default type of integer, while variables starting with any other letters defaulted to real, although programmers could override the defaults with an explicit declaration.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The **IBM System/360** (**S/360**) is a family of computer systems announced by IBM on April 7, 1964, and delivered between 1965 and 1978.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] System/360 was the first family of computers designed to cover both commercial and scientific applications and a complete range of sizes from small, entry-level machines to large mainframes.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The design distinguished between architecture and implementation, allowing IBM to release a suite of compatible designs at different prices.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] All but the only partially compatible Model 44 and the most expensive systems use microcode to implement the instruction set, which used 8-bit byte addressing with fixed-point binary, fixed-point decimal and hexadecimal floating-point calculations.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The System/360 family introduced IBM's Solid Logic Technology (SLT), which packed more transistors onto a circuit card, allowing more powerful but smaller computers, but did not include integrated circuits, which IBM considered too immature.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] System/360's chief architect was Gene Amdahl and the project was managed by Fred Brooks, responsible to Chairman Thomas J.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The commercial release was piloted by another of Watson's lieutenants, John R.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Opel, who managed the launch of IBM's System/360 mainframe family in 1964.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The slowest System/360 model announced in 1964, the Model 30, could perform up to 34,500 instructions per second, with memory from 8 to 64 KB.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 1967 IBM System/360 Model 91 could execute up to 16.6 million instructions per second.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The larger 360 models could have up to 8 MB of main memory, though that much memory was unusual; a large installation might have as little as 256 KB of main storage, but 512 KB, 768 KB or 1024 KB was more common.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Up to 8 megabytes of slower (8 microsecond) Large Capacity Storage (LCS) was also available for some models.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The IBM 360 was extremely successful, allowing customers to purchase a smaller system knowing they could expand it, if their needs grew, without reprogramming application software or replacing peripheral devices.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] It influenced computer design for years to come; many consider it one of history's most successful computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Application-level compatibility (with some restrictions) for System/360 software is maintained to the present day with the IBM Z mainframe servers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] By the early 1960s, IBM was struggling with the load of supporting and upgrading five separate lines of computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These were aimed at different market segments and were entirely different from each other.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A customer who purchased a machine to handle accounting, such as the IBM 1401, that was now looking for a machine for engineering calculations, such as the IBM 7040, had no reason to select IBM – the 7040 was incompatible with the 1401 and they might as well have been from different companies.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Customers were frustrated that major investments, often entirely new machines and programs, were required when seemingly small performance improvements were needed.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In 1961, IBM assembled a task force to chart their developments for the 1960s, known as SPREAD, for Systems Programming, Research, Engineering and Development.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In meetings at the New Englander Motor Hotel in Greenwich, Connecticut, SPREAD developed a new concept for the next generation of IBM machines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] At the time, new technologies were coming into the market including the introduction of replacement of individual transistors with small-scale integrated circuits and the move to an 8-bit byte from the former 6-bit oriented words.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These were going to lead to a new generation of machines, today known as the third generation, from all of the existing vendors.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Where SPREAD differed significantly from previous concepts was what features would be supported.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Instead of machines aimed at different market niches, the new concept was effectively the union of all of these designs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A single instruction set architecture (ISA) included instructions for binary, floating-point, and decimal arithmetic, string processing, conversion between character sets (a major issue before the widespread use of ASCII) and extensive support for file handling, among many other features.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This would mean IBM would be introducing yet another line of machines, once again incompatible with their earlier machines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] But the new systems would be able to run all of the programs that formerly required different machines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A concern was that there was a risk that their customers, facing the purchase of yet another new and incompatible platform, would simply choose some other vendor.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Yet the concept steadily gained support, and six months after being formed, the company decided to implement the SPREAD concept.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A new team was organized under the direction of Bob Evans, who personally persuaded CEO Thomas J.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Gene Amdahl was the chief architect of the computers themselves, while Fred Brooks was the project lead for the software and Erich Bloch led the development of IBM's hybrid integrated circuit designs, Solid Logic Technology.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Producing a single system design with support for all of these features, at a price acceptable to low-end customers and with a performance level acceptable to high-end customers, would border on impossible.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Instead, the SPREAD concept was based on the separation of the defined feature set from its internal operation, with a family of machines with different performance and different internal designs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Specifically, depending on the machine, some components might not be directly implemented in hardware, and would instead be completed using small programs referred to as microcode or microprograms.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These small programs, or subprograms, would be stored in read only memory (ROM) inside the machine.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Some models use microcode in the central processing unit (CPU) to implement instructions while others use only hardware.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Some models use cycle-stealing microcode in the CPU to implement I/O channels while others use only hardware in separate units.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Today this approach is known as microcode.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This meant that a single lineup could have machines tailored to match the price and performance niches that formerly demanded entirely separate computer systems, where software was specific to each system.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This flexibility greatly lowered barriers to entry.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] With most other vendors customers had to choose between machines they might outgrow or machines that were potentially too powerful and thus too costly.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In practice, this meant that many companies simply did not buy computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Now, a customer could purchase a machine that solved a particular requirement, knowing they could switch models as their needs changed, without losing support for the programs they were already running.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] For instance, in the case of a firm that purchased an accounting system and was now looking to expand their computer support into engineering, this meant they could develop and test their engineering program on the machine they already used.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] If they ever needed more performance, they could purchase a machine with floating-point hardware, knowing that nothing else would change, it would simply get faster.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Even the same peripherals could be used, allowing, for instance, data from the engineering system to be written to tape and then printed using a high-speed line printer already connected to their accounting system.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Or they might replace the accounting system outright with a system with the performance to run both tasks.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The idea that a single design could address all the myriad ways that the machines could be used gave rise to the name, "360" is a reference to 360 degrees in a circle, and circles of machines and components featured prominently in IBM's advertising.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM initially announced a series of six computers and forty common peripherals.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM eventually delivered fourteen models, including rare one-off models for NASA.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The least expensive model was the Model 20 with as little as 4096 bytes of core memory, eight 16-bit registers instead of the sixteen 32-bit registers of other System/360 models, and an instruction set that was a subset of that used by the rest of the range.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The first three were low- to middle-range systems aimed at the IBM 1400 series market.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The last three, intended to replace the 7000 series machines, never shipped and were replaced with the 65 and 75, which were first delivered in November 1965, and January 1966, respectively.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 20 had several sub-models; sub-model 5 was at the higher end of the model.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 22 was a recycled Model 30 with minor limitations: a smaller maximum memory configuration, and slower I/O channels, which limited it to slower and lower-capacity disk and tape devices than on the 30.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 44 (1966) was a specialized model, designed for scientific computing and for real-time computing and process control, featuring some additional instructions, and with all storage-to-storage instructions and five other complex instructions eliminated.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 85 design was intermediate between the System/360 line and the follow-on System/370 and was the basis for the 370/165.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] There was a System/370 version of the 195, but it did not include Dynamic Address Translation.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The implementations differed substantially, using different native data path widths, presence or absence of microcode, yet were extremely compatible.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Except where specifically documented, the models were architecturally compatible.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 91, for example, was designed for scientific computing and provided out-of-order instruction execution (and could yield "imprecise interrupts" if a program trap occurred while several instructions were being read), but lacked the decimal instruction set used in commercial applications.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] New features could be added without violating architectural definitions: the 65 had a dual-processor version (M65MP) with extensions for inter-CPU signalling; the 85 introduced cache memory.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Models 44, 75, 91, 95, and 195 were implemented with hardwired logic, rather than microcoded as all other models.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 67, announced in August 1965, was the first production IBM system to offer dynamic address translation (virtual memory) hardware to support time-sharing.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] "DAT" is now more commonly referred to as an MMU.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] An experimental one-off unit was built based on a model 40.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Before the 67, IBM had announced models 64 and 66, DAT versions of the 60 and 62, but they were almost immediately replaced with the 67 at the same time that the 60 and 62 were replaced with the 65.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] DAT hardware would reappear in the S/370 series in 1972, though it was initially absent from the series.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Like its close relative, the 65, the 67 also offered dual CPUs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM stopped marketing all System/360 models by the end of 1977.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM's existing customers had a large investment in software that ran on second-generation machines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Several System/360 models had the option of emulating the customer's existing computer using special hardware and microcode, and an emulation program that enabled existing programs to run on the new machine.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Customers initially had to halt the computer and load the emulation program.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM later added features and modified emulator programs to allow emulation of the 1401, 1440, 1460, 1410 and 7010 under the control of an operating system.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 85 and later System/370 maintained the precedent, retaining emulation options and allowing emulators to run under OS control alongside native programs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] System/360 (excepting the Models 20, 44 and 67) was replaced with the mostly compatible System/370 range in 1970 and Model 20 users were targeted to move to the IBM System/3.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] (The idea of a major breakthrough with FS technology was dropped in the mid-1970s for cost-effectiveness and continuity reasons.) Later compatible IBM systems include the 4300 family, the 308x family, the 3090, the ES/9000 and 9672 families (System/390 family), and the IBM Z series.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The IBM 5100 portable computer, introduced in 1975, offered an option to execute the System/360's APL.SV programming language through a hardware emulator.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM used this approach to avoid the costs and delay of creating a 5100-specific version of APL.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Special radiation-hardened and otherwise somewhat modified System/360s, in the form of the System/4 Pi avionics computer, are used in several fighter and bomber jet aircraft.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In the complete 32-bit AP-101 version, 4 Pi machines were used as the replicated computing nodes of the fault-tolerant Space Shuttle computer system (in five nodes).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Federal Aviation Administration operated the IBM 9020, a special cluster of modified System/360s for air traffic control, from 1970 until the 1990s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] 16–32 KB cache memory, extended-precision floating point.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The System/360 series computer architecture specification makes no assumptions on the implementation itself, but rather describes the interfaces and expected behavior of an implementation.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The architecture describes mandatory interfaces that must be available on all implementations, and optional interfaces.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] All models of System/360, except for the Model 20 and Model 44, implemented that specification.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Binary arithmetic and logical operations are performed as register-to-register and as memory-to-register/register-to-memory as a standard feature.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] If the Commercial Instruction Set option was installed, packed decimal arithmetic could be performed as memory-to-memory with some memory-to-register operations.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Scientific Instruction Set feature, if installed, provided access to four floating-point registers that could be programmed for either 32-bit or 64-bit floating-point operations.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Models 85 and 195 could also operate on 128-bit extended-precision floating-point numbers stored in pairs of floating-point registers, and software provided emulation in other models.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The System/360 used an 8-bit byte, 32-bit word, 64-bit double-word, and 4-bit nibble.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Machine instructions had operators with operands, which could contain register numbers or memory addresses.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This complex combination of instruction options resulted in a variety of instruction lengths and formats.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Memory addressing was accomplished using a base-plus-displacement scheme, with registers 1 through F (15).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A displacement was encoded in 12 bits, thus allowing a 4096-byte displacement (0–4095), as the offset from the address put in a base register.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This specific behavior permitted initial execution of an interrupt routines, since base registers would not necessarily be set to 0 during the first few instruction cycles of an interrupt routine.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] It isn't needed for IPL ("Initial Program Load" or boot), as one can always clear a register without the need to save it.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] With the exception of the Model 67, all addresses were real memory addresses.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Virtual memory was not available in most IBM mainframes until the System/370 series.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 67 introduced a virtual memory architecture, which MTS, CP-67, and TSS/360 used—but not IBM's mainline System/360 operating systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The System/360 machine-code instructions are 2 bytes long (no memory operands), 4 bytes long (one operand), or 6 bytes long (two operands).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Instructions are always situated on 2-byte boundaries.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Operations like MVC (Move-Characters) (Hex: D2) can only move at most 256 bytes of information.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Moving more than 256 bytes of data required multiple MVC operations.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] An operand is two bytes long, typically representing an address as a 4-bit nibble denoting a base register and a 12-bit displacement relative to the contents of that register, in the range 000–FFF (shown here as hexadecimal numbers).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The address corresponding to that operand is the contents of the specified general-purpose register plus the displacement.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] For example, an MVC instruction that moves 256 bytes (with length code 255 in hexadecimal as FF) from base register 7, plus displacement 000, to base register 8, plus displacement 001, would be coded as the 6-byte instruction "D2FF 8001 7000" (operator/length/address1/address2).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The System/360 was designed to separate the *supervisor state* from the *problem state*.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This provided a basic level of security and recoverability from programming errors.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Problem (user) programs could not modify data or program storage associated with the supervisor state.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Addressing, data, or operation exception errors made the machine enter the supervisor state through a controlled routine so the operating system could try to correct or terminate the program in error.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Similarly, it could recover certain processor hardware errors through the *machine check* routines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Peripherals interfaced to the system via *channels*.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A channel is a specialized processor with the instruction set optimized for transferring data between a peripheral and main memory.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In modern terms, this could be compared to direct memory access (DMA).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The S/360 connects channels to control units with bus and tag cables; IBM eventually replaced these with Enterprise Systems Connection (ESCON) and Fibre Connection (FICON) channels, but well after the S/360 era.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Every System/360 (except for the Model 20, which was not a standard 360) has a byte-multiplexer channel and 1 or more selector channels, though the model 25 has just one channel, which can be either a byte-multiplexor or selector channel.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The byte-multiplexer channel is able to handle I/O to/from several devices simultaneously at the device's highest rated speeds, hence the name, as it multiplexed I/O from those devices onto a single data path to main memory.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Devices connected to a byte-multiplexer channel are configured to operate in 1-byte, 2-byte, 4-byte, or "burst" mode.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The larger "blocks" of data are used to handle progressively faster devices.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] For example, a 2501 card reader operating at 600 cards per minute would be in 1-byte mode, while a 1403-N1 printer would be in burst mode.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Also, the byte-multiplexer channels on larger models have an optional selector subchannel section that would accommodate tape drives.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The byte-multiplexor's channel address was typically "0" and the selector subchannel addresses were from "C0" to "FF." Thus, tape drives on System/360 were commonly addressed at 0C0–0C7.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These addresses are still commonly used in z/VM virtual machines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] System/360 models 40 and 50 have an integrated 1052-7 console that is usually addressed as 01F, however, this was not connected to the byte-multiplexer channel, but rather, had a direct internal connection to the mainframe.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The model 30 attached a different model of 1052 through a 1051 control unit.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The models 60 through 75 also use the 1052–7.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Selector channels enabled I/O to high speed devices.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These storage devices were attached to a control unit and then to the channel.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The control unit let clusters of devices be attached to the channels.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] On higher speed models, multiple selector channels, which could operate simultaneously or in parallel, improved overall performance.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Control units are connected to the channels with "bus and tag" cable pairs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The bus cables carried the address and data information and the tag cables identified what data was on the bus.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The general configuration of a channel is to connect the devices in a chain, like this: Mainframe—Control Unit X—Control Unit Y—Control Unit Z.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Each control unit is assigned a "capture range" of addresses that it services.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] For example, control unit X might capture addresses 40–4F, control unit Y: C0–DF, and control unit Z: 80–9F.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Capture ranges had to be a multiple of 8, 16, 32, 64, or 128 devices and be aligned on appropriate boundaries.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Each control unit in turn has one or more devices attached to it.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] For example, you could have control unit Y with 6 disks, that would be addressed as C0-C5.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] There are three general types of bus-and-tag cables produced by IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The first is the standard gray bus-and-tag cable, followed by the blue bus-and-tag cable, and finally the tan bus-and-tag cable.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Generally, newer cable revisions are capable of higher speeds or longer distances, and some peripherals specified minimum cable revisions both upstream and downstream.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The cable ordering of the control units on the channel is also significant.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Each control unit is "strapped" as High or Low priority.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] When a device selection was sent out on a mainframe's channel, the selection was sent from X->Y->Z->Y->X.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] If the control unit was "high" then the selection was checked in the outbound direction, if "low" then the inbound direction.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Thus, control unit X was either 1st or 5th, Y was either 2nd or 4th, and Z was 3rd in line.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] It is also possible to have multiple channels attached to a control unit from the same or multiple mainframes, thus providing a rich high-performance, multiple-access, and backup capability.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Typically the total cable length of a channel is limited to 200 feet, less being preferred.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Each control unit accounts for about 10 "feet" of the 200-foot limit.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM first introduced a new type of I/O channel on the Model 85 and Model 195, the 2880 block multiplexer channel, and then made them standard on the System/370.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This channel allowed a device to suspend a channel program, pending the completion of an I/O operation and thus to free the channel for use by another device.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A block multiplexer channel can support either standard 1.5 MB/s connections or, with the 2-byte interface feature, 3 MB/s; the latter use one tag cable and two bus cables.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] On the S/370 there is an option for a 3.0 MB/s data streaming channel with one bus cable and one tag cable.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The initial use for this was the 2305 fixed-head disk, which has 8 "exposures" (alias addresses) and rotational position sensing (RPS).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Block multiplexer channels can operate as a selector channel to allow compatible attachment of legacy subsystems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Being uncertain of the reliability and availability of the then new monolithic integrated circuits, IBM chose instead to design and manufacture its own custom hybrid integrated circuits.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These were built on 11 mm square ceramic substrates.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Resistors were silk screened on and discrete glass encapsulated transistors and diodes were added.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The substrate was then covered with a metal lid or encapsulated in plastic to create a "Solid Logic Technology" (SLT) module.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A number of these SLT modules were then flip chip mounted onto a small multi-layer printed circuit "SLT card".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Each card had one or two sockets on one edge that plugged onto pins on one of the computer's "SLT boards" (also referred to as a backplane).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This was the reverse of how most other company's cards were mounted, where the cards had pins or printed contact areas and plugged into sockets on the computer's boards.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Up to twenty SLT boards could be assembled side-by-side (vertically and horizontally, max 4 high by 5 wide) to form a "logic gate".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Several gates mounted together constituted a box-shaped "logic frame".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The outer gates were generally hinged along one vertical edge so they could be swung open to provide access to the fixed inner gates.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The larger machines could have more than one frame bolted together to produce the final unit, such as a multi-frame Central Processing Unit (CPU).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The smaller System/360 models used the Basic Operating System/360 (BOS/360), Tape Operating System (TOS/360), or Disk Operating System/360 (DOS/360, which evolved into DOS/VS, DOS/VSE, VSE/AF, VSE/SP, VSE/ESA, and then z/VSE).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The larger models used Operating System/360 (OS/360).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM developed several levels of OS/360, with increasingly powerful features: Primary Control Program (PCP), Multiprogramming with a Fixed number of Tasks (MFT), and Multiprogramming with a Variable number of Tasks (MVT).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] MVT took a long time to develop into a usable system, and the less ambitious MFT was widely used.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] PCP was used on intermediate machines too small to run MFT well, and on larger machines before MFT was available; the final releases of OS/360 included only MFT and MVT.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] For the System/370 and later machines, MFT evolved into OS/VS1, while MVT evolved into OS/VS2 (SVS) (Single Virtual Storage), then various versions of MVS (Multiple Virtual Storage) culminating in the current z/OS.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] When it announced the Model 67 in August 1965, IBM also announced TSS/360 (Time-Sharing System) for delivery at the same time as the 67.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] TSS/360, a response to Multics, was an ambitious project that included many advanced features.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] It had performance problems, was delayed, canceled, reinstated, and finally canceled again in 1971.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Customers migrated to CP-67, MTS (Michigan Terminal System), TSO (Time Sharing Option for OS/360), or one of several other time-sharing systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] CP-67, the original virtual machine system, was also known as CP/CMS.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] CP/67 was developed outside the IBM mainstream at IBM's Cambridge Scientific Center, in cooperation with MIT researchers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] CP/CMS eventually won wide acceptance, and led to the development of VM/370 (Virtual Machine) which had a primary interactive "sub" operating system known as VM/CMS (Conversational Monitoring System).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 20 offered a simplified and rarely used tape-based system called TPS (Tape Processing System), and DPS (Disk Processing System) that provided support for the 2311 disk drive.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] TPS could run on a machine with 8 KB of memory; DPS required 12 KB, which was pretty hefty for a Model 20.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Many customers ran quite happily with 4 KB and CPS (Card Processing System).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] With TPS and DPS, the card reader was used to read the Job Control Language cards that defined the stack of jobs to run and to read in transaction data such as customer payments.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The operating system was held on tape or disk, and results could also be stored on the tapes or hard drives.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Stacked job processing became an exciting possibility for the small but adventurous computer user.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A little-known and little-used suite of 80-column punched-card utility programs known as Basic Programming Support (BPS) (jocularly: Barely Programming Support), a precursor of TOS, was available for smaller systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM created a new naming system for the new components created for System/360, although well-known old names, like IBM 1403 and IBM 1052, were retained.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In this new naming system, components were given four-digit numbers starting with 2.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] IBM developed a new family of peripheral equipment for System/360, carrying over a few from its older 1400 series.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Interfaces were standardized, allowing greater flexibility to mix and match processors, controllers and peripherals than in the earlier product lines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In addition, System/360 computers could use certain peripherals that were originally developed for earlier computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These earlier peripherals used a different numbering system, such as the IBM 1403 chain printer.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 1403, an extremely reliable device that had already earned a reputation as a workhorse, was sold as the 1403-N1 when adapted for the System/360.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Also available were optical character recognition (OCR) readers IBM 1287 and IBM 1288 which could read Alpha Numeric (A/N) and Numeric Hand Printed (NHP/NHW) Characters from Cashier's rolls of tape to full legal size pages.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] At the time this was done with very large optical/logic readers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Software was too slow and expensive at that time.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Models 65 and below sold with an IBM 1052–7 as the console typewriter.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 360/85 with feature 5450 uses a display console that was not compatible with anything else in the line; the later 3066 console for the 370/165 and 370/168 use the same basic display design as the 360/85.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The IBM System/360 models 91 and 195 use a graphical display similar to the IBM 2250 as their primary console.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Additional operator consoles were also available.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Certain high-end machines could optionally be purchased with a 2250 graphical display, costing upwards of US$100,000; smaller machines could use the less expensive 2260 display or later the 3270.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The first disk drives for System/360 were IBM 2302s and IBM 2311s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The first drum for System/360 was the IBM 7320.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 156 kbit/s 2302 was based on the earlier 1302 and was available as a model 3 with two 112.79 MB modules or as a model 4 with four such modules.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 2311, with a removable 1316 disk pack, was based on the IBM 1311 and had a theoretical capacity of 7.2 MB, although actual capacity varied with record design.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This device had up to eight usable disk drives with an integral control unit; there were nine drives, but one was reserved as a spare.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Each drive used a removable 2316 disk pack with a capacity of nearly 28 MB.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The disk packs for the 2311 and 2314 were *physically* large by today's standards — e.g., the 1316 disk pack was about 14 in (36 cm) in diameter and had six platters stacked on a central spindle.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The top and bottom outside platters did not store data.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Data were recorded on the inner sides of the top and bottom platters and both sides of the inner platters, providing 10 recording surfaces.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 10 read/write heads moved together across the surfaces of the platters, which were formatted with 203 concentric tracks.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] To reduce the amount of head movement (seeking), data was written in a virtual cylinder from inside top platter down to inside bottom platter.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These disks were not usually formatted with fixed-sized sectors as are today's hard drives (though this *was* done with CP/CMS).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Rather, most System/360 I/O software could customize the length of the data record (variable-length records), as was the case with magnetic tapes.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Some of the most powerful early System/360s used high-speed head-per-track drum storage devices.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 3,500 RPM 2301, which replaced the 7320, was part of the original System/360 announcement, with a capacity of 4 MB.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 303.8 kbit/s IBM 2303 was announced on January 31, 1966, with a capacity of 3.913 MB.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] These were the only drums announced for System/360 and System/370, and their niche was later filled by fixed-head disks.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Although these devices did not have large capacity, their speed and transfer rates made them attractive for high-performance needs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A typical use was overlay linkage (e.g. for OS and application subroutines) for program sections written to alternate in the same memory regions.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Fixed-head disks and drums were particularly effective as paging devices on the early virtual memory systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 2305, although often called a "drum" was actually a head-per-track disk device, with 12 recording surfaces and a data transfer rate up to 3 MB/s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Rarely seen was the IBM 2321 Data Cell, a mechanically complex device that contained multiple magnetic strips to hold data; strips could be randomly accessed, placed upon a cylinder-shaped drum for read/write operations; then returned to an internal storage cartridge.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The IBM Data Cell [noodle picker] was among several IBM trademarked "speedy" mass online direct-access storage peripherals (reincarnated in recent years as "virtual tape" and automated tape librarian peripherals).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 2321 file had a capacity of 400 MB, at the time when the 2311 disk drive only had 7.2 MB.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The IBM Data Cell was proposed to fill cost/capacity/speed gap between magnetic tapes—which had high capacity with relatively low cost per stored byte—and disks, which had higher expense per byte.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Some installations also found the electromechanical operation less dependable and opted for less mechanical forms of direct-access storage.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The Model 44 was unique in offering an integrated single-disk drive as a standard feature.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This drive used the 2315 "ramkit" cartridge and provided 1,171,200 bytes of storage.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 2400-series of 1/2" magnetic tape units consisted of the 2401 and 2402 Models 1-6 Magnetic Tape Units, the 2403 Models 1-6 Magnetic Tape Unit and Control, the 2404 Models 1-3 Magnetic Tape Unit and Control, and the 2803/2804 Models 1 and 2 Tape Control Units.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The later 2415 Magnetic Tape Unit and Control, introduced in 1967 contained two, four, or six tape drives and a control in a single unit, and was slower and cheaper.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] The 2415 drives and control were not marketed separately.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] With System/360, IBM switched from IBM 7-track to 9-track tape format.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Some 2400-series drives could be purchased that read and wrote 7-track tapes for compatibility with the older IBM 729 tape drives.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] In 1968, the IBM 2420 tape system was released, offering much higher data rates, self-threading tape operation and 1600bpi packing density.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] It remained in the product line until 1979.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] Despite having been sold or leased in very large numbers for a mainframe system of its era, only a few of System/360 computers remain—mainly as non-operating property of museums or collectors.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] A running list of remaining System/360s that are more than just 'front panels' can be found at World Inventory of remaining System/360 CPUs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm-system-360] This gallery shows the operator's console, with register indicator lamps, toggle switches (middle of pictures), and "emergency pull" switch (upper right of pictures) of the various models.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM was founded in 1911 as the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR), a holding company of manufacturers of record-keeping and measuring systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] It was renamed "International Business Machines" in 1924 and soon became the leading manufacturer of punch-card tabulating systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] During the 1960s and 1970s, the IBM mainframe, exemplified by the System/360 and its successors, was the world's dominant computing platform, with the company producing 80 percent of computers in the U.S. and 70 percent of computers worldwide.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Embracing both business and scientific computing, System/360 was the first family of computers designed to cover a complete range of applications from small to large.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM entered the microcomputer market in 1981 with the IBM Personal Computer; its architecture remains the basis for the majority of personal computers sold today.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company later also found success in the laptop space with the ThinkPad.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Since the 1990s, IBM has concentrated on computer services, software, supercomputers, and scientific research; it sold its microcomputer division to Lenovo in 2005.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM continues to develop mainframes, and its supercomputers have consistently ranked among the most powerful in the world in the 21st century.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company has made inroads in advanced computer chips, quantum computing, artificial intelligence, and data infrastructure.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM employees and alumni have won various recognitions for their scientific research and inventions, including six Nobel Prizes and six Turing Awards.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM originated with several technological innovations developed and commercialized in the late 19th century.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Pitrap patented the computing scale in 1885; Alexander Dey invented the dial recorder (1888); Herman Hollerith patented the Electric Tabulating Machine (1889); and Willard Bundy invented a time clock to record workers' arrival and departure times on a paper tape (1889).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On June 16, 1911, their four companies were amalgamated in New York State by Charles Ranlett Flint forming a fifth company, the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR) based in Endicott, New York.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The five companies had 1,300 employees and offices and plants in Endicott and Binghamton, New York; Dayton, Ohio; Detroit, Michigan; Washington, D.C.; and Toronto, Canada.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Collectively, the companies manufactured a wide array of machinery for sale and lease, ranging from commercial scales and industrial time recorders, meat and cheese slicers, to tabulators and punched cards.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watson, Sr., fired from the National Cash Register Company (NCR) by John Henry Patterson, called on Flint and, in 1914, was offered a position at CTR.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watson joined CTR as general manager and then, 11 months later, was made President when antitrust cases relating to his time at NCR were resolved.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Having learned Patterson's pioneering business practices, Watson proceeded to put the stamp of NCR onto CTR's companies.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] He implemented sales conventions, "generous sales incentives, a focus on customer service, an insistence on well-groomed, dark-suited salesmen and had an evangelical fervor for instilling company pride and loyalty in every worker".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] His favorite slogan, "THINK", became a mantra for each company's employees.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] During Watson's first four years, revenues reached $9 million ($167 million today) and the company's operations expanded to Europe, South America, Asia and Australia.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watson never liked the clumsy hyphenated name "Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company" and chose to replace it with the more expansive title "International Business Machines" which had previously been used as the name of CTR's Canadian Division; the name was changed on February 14, 1924.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] By 1933, most of the subsidiaries had been merged into one company, IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The Nazis made extensive use of Hollerith punch card and alphabetical accounting equipment and IBM's majority-owned German subsidiary, Deutsche Hollerith Maschinen GmbH (Dehomag), supplied this equipment from the early 1930s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] This equipment was critical to Nazi efforts to categorize citizens of both Germany and other nations that fell under Nazi control through ongoing censuses.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] These census data were used to facilitate the round-up of Jews and other targeted groups, and to catalog their movements through the machinery of the Holocaust, including internment in the concentration camps.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Edwin Black contends in *IBM and the Holocaust* that IBM's dealings with Nazis through its New York City headquarters persisted during World War II.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Nazi concentration camps operated a Hollerith department called Hollerith Abteilung, which had IBM machines, including calculating and sorting machines.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM as a military contractor produced 6% of the M1 Carbine rifles used in World War II, about 346,500 of them, between August 1943 and May 1944.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM built the Automatic Sequence Controlled Calculator, an electromechanical computer, during World War II.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] It offered its first commercial stored-program computer, the vacuum tube based IBM 701, in 1952.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The IBM 305 RAMAC introduced the hard disk drive in 1956.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company switched to transistorized designs with the 7000 and 1400 series, beginning in 1958.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The 1400 series was the first to deploy over 10000 units, making it its most successful computer device at the time.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1956, the company demonstrated the first practical example of artificial intelligence when Arthur L.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Samuel of IBM's Poughkeepsie, New York, laboratory programmed an IBM 704 not merely to play checkers but "learn" from its own experience.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1957, the FORTRAN scientific programming language was announced.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1961, IBM developed the SABRE reservation system for American Airlines and introduced the highly successful Selectric typewriter.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Also in 1961, IBM used the IBM 7094 to generate the first song sung completely by a computer using synthesizers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The song was Daisy Bell (Bicycle Built for Two).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The recording is now in the United States National Recording Registry.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1963, IBM employees and computers helped NASA track the orbital flights of the Mercury astronauts.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] A year later, it moved its corporate headquarters from New York City to Armonk, New York.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The latter half of the 1960s saw IBM continue its support of space exploration, participating in the 1965 Gemini flights, 1966 Saturn flights, and 1969 lunar mission.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM also developed and manufactured the Saturn V's Instrument Unit and Apollo spacecraft guidance computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On April 7, 1964, IBM launched the first computer system family, the IBM System/360.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] It spanned the complete range of commercial and scientific applications from large to small, allowing companies for the first time to upgrade to models with greater computing capability without having to rewrite their applications.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] It was followed by the IBM System/370 in 1970.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Together the 360 and 370 made the IBM mainframe the dominant mainframe computer and the dominant computing platform in the industry throughout this period and into the early 1980s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] They and the operating systems that ran on them such as OS/VS1 and MVS, and the middleware built on top of those such as the CICS transaction processing monitor, had a near-monopoly-level market share and became the thing IBM was most known for during this period.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Shortly after, IBM unbundled its software and services in what many observers believed was a direct result of the lawsuit, creating a competitive market for software.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1982, the Department of Justice dropped the case as "without merit".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Also in 1969, IBM engineer Forrest Parry invented the magnetic stripe card that would become ubiquitous for credit/debit/ATM cards, driver's licenses, rapid transit cards and a multitude of other identity and access control applications.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM pioneered the manufacture of these cards, and for most of the 1970s, the data processing systems and software for such applications ran exclusively on IBM computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Laurer developed the Universal Product Code.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM and the World Bank first introduced financial swaps to the public in 1981, when it entered into a swap agreement.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In the early 1970s, the Examination Department of the South Vietnamese Ministry of Education contracted with IBM to computerize all examination records, from registration and application forms to certificates of admission and necessary statistical data.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] By 1974, all subjects in the South Vietnamese high school graduation exam were converted to multiple-choice questions.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Answer sheets for the multiple-choice exams were ordered from the United States, and candidates' papers were graded using an IBM 1230 machine.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The graded papers were then transferred to an IBM 534 machine for punching.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] These punched sheets were then fed into an IBM 360 machine to read the scores, multiply by coefficients, add up the scores, calculate the average score, standard deviation, convert raw scores to standardized scores, and calculate the admission ranking.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The sample group and norm group were carefully selected according to statistical methods to calculate the average score and standard deviation.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM entered the microcomputer market in the 1980s with the IBM Personal Computer (IBM 5150).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The computer, which spawned a long line of successors, had a profound influence on the development of the personal computer market and became one of IBM's best selling products of all time.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The PC was not well protected by intellectual property laws.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] As a consequence, IBM quickly began losing its market dominance to emerging, compatible competitors in the PC market.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Experts debate whether this was an early example of successful adoption of open architecture, or a lack of business foresight by IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1985, IBM collaborated with Microsoft to develop a new operating system, which was released as OS/2.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Following a dispute, Microsoft severed the collaboration and IBM continued development of OS/2 on its own but it failed in the marketplace against Microsoft's Windows during the mid-1990s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1991, IBM began spinning off its many divisions into autonomous subsidiaries (so-called "Baby Blues") in an attempt to make the company more manageable and to streamline IBM by having other investors finance those companies.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Lexmark was acquired by Clayton & Dubilier in a leveraged buyout shortly after its formation.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1997, Deep Blue, a chess computer created by IBM beat Chess World Champion at the time, Garry Kasparov in a six round match following standard tournament rules.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In September 1992, IBM finished spinning off its various microcomputer personal computer manufacturing divisions and were consolidated into an autonomous wholly owned subsidiary known as the IBM Personal Computer Company (IBM PC Co.).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] This corporate restructuring came after IBM reported a sharp drop in profit margins during the second quarter of fiscal year 1992; market analysts attributed the drop to a fierce price war in the personal computer market over the summer of 1992.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The corporate restructuring was one of the largest and most expensive in history up to that point.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM PC Co. introduced the ThinkPad clone computers, which IBM would heavily market and would eventually become one of the best-selling series of notebook computers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1993, IBM posted an $8 billion loss – at the time the biggest in American corporate history.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Lou Gerstner was hired as CEO from RJR Nabisco to turn the company around.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1995, IBM purchased Lotus Development Corporation, best known for its Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet software.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] During the decade, IBM was working on a new operating system, named the Workplace OS project.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Despite a large amount of money spent on the project, it was cancelled in 1996.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1998, IBM merged the enterprise-oriented Personal Systems Group of the IBM PC Co. into IBM's own Global Services personal computer consulting and customer service division.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The resulting merged business units then became known simply as IBM Personal Systems Group.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] A year later, IBM stopped selling its computers at retail outlets after its market share in this sector had fallen considerably behind competitors Compaq and Dell.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Immediately afterwards, the IBM PC Co. was dissolved and merged into IBM Personal Systems Group.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In the 2000s, IBM collaborated with the Chinese defense contractor Huadi to develop the “Golden Shield Project”, a large-scale policing and surveillance project in Beijing.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The system was reportedly used to monitor online activity and target groups such as Falun Gong, Uyghurs and other individuals considered security risks.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2002, IBM acquired PwC Consulting, the consulting arm of PwC which was merged into its IBM Global Services.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On September 14, 2004, LG and IBM announced that their business alliance in the South Korean market would end at the end of that year.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Both companies stated that it was unrelated to the charges of bribery earlier that year.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Xnote was originally part of the joint venture and was sold by LG in 2012.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Continuing a trend started in the 1990s of downsizing its operations and divesting from commodity production, IBM sold all of its personal computer business to Chinese technology company Lenovo, and in 2009, it acquired software company SPSS Inc.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Later in 2009, IBM's Blue Gene supercomputing program was awarded the National Medal of Technology and Innovation by U.S.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2011, an IBM-owned artificial intelligence program called Watson was exhibited on *Jeopardy!* where it won against game-show champions Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company also celebrated its 100th anniversary in the same year on June 16.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2012, IBM announced it had agreed to buy Kenexa and Texas Memory Systems, and a year later it also acquired SoftLayer Technologies, a web hosting service, in a deal worth around $2 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Also that year, the company designed a video surveillance system for Davao City.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2014, IBM announced it would sell its x86 server division to Lenovo for $2.1 billion while continuing to offer Power ISA-based servers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Also that year, IBM began announcing several major partnerships with other companies, including Apple Inc., Twitter, Facebook, Tencent, Cisco, UnderArmour, Box, Microsoft, VMware, CSC, Macy's, Sesame Workshop, the parent company of Sesame Street, and Salesforce.com.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2015, its chip division transitioned to a fabless model with semiconductors design, offloading manufacturing to GlobalFoundries.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2015, IBM announced three major acquisitions: Merge Healthcare for $1 billion, data storage vendor Cleversafe, and all digital assets from The Weather Company, including Weather.com and The Weather Channel mobile app.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Also that year, IBM employees created the film *A Boy and His Atom*, which was the first molecule movie to tell a story.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2016, IBM acquired video conferencing service Ustream and formed a new cloud video unit.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In April 2016, it posted a 14-year low in quarterly sales.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The following month, Groupon sued IBM accusing it of patent infringement, two months after IBM accused Groupon of patent infringement in a separate lawsuit.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2016, IBM bought Truven Health Analytics for $2.6 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In October 2018, IBM announced its intention to acquire Red Hat for $34 billion, which was completed on July 9, 2019.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In February 2020, IBM's John Kelly III joined Brad Smith of Microsoft to sign a pledge with the Vatican to ensure the ethical use and practice of Artificial Intelligence (AI).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM announced in October 2020 that it would divest the Managed Infrastructure Services unit of its Global Technology Services division into a new public company.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The new company, Kyndryl, will have 90,000 employees, 4,600 clients in 115 countries, with an order backlog of $60 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's spin-off was greater than any of its previous divestitures, and welcomed by investors.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM appointed Martin Schroeter, who had been IBM's CFO from 2014 through the end of 2017, as CEO of Kyndryl.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2021, IBM announced the acquisition of the enterprise software company Turbonomic for $1.5 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In January 2022, IBM announced it would sell Watson Health to private equity firm Francisco Partners.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On March 7, 2022, a few days after the start of the Russian invasion of Ukraine, IBM CEO Arvind Krishna announced that "we have suspended all business in Russia".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] All Russian articles were also removed from the IBM website.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On June 7, Krishna announced that IBM would carry out an "orderly wind-down" of its operations in Russia.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In late 2022, IBM started a collaboration with new Japanese manufacturer Rapidus, which led GlobalFoundries to file a lawsuit against IBM the following year.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2023, IBM acquired Manta Software Inc. to complement its data and A.I. governance capabilities for an undisclosed amount.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On November 16, 2023, IBM suspended ads on Twitter after ads were found next to pro-Nazi content.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In August 2023, IBM agreed to sell The Weather Company to Francisco Partners for an undisclosed sum.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The sale was finalized on February 1, 2024, and the price was disclosed as $1.1 billion, with $750 million in cash, $100 million deferred over seven years, and $250 million in contingent consideration.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In December 2023, IBM announced it would acquire Software AG's StreamSets and webMethods platforms for €2.13 billion ($2.33 billion).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On December 8, 2025, IBM announced a deal to acquire data-infrastructure company Confluent for approximately $11 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The deal closed in March 2026 and was expected to help further advance the company's interests in AI.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] On June 25, 2026, IBM unveiled the world's first technology capable of producing chips smaller than 1 nanometer.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's market capitalization was valued at over $153 billion as of May 2024.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Despite its relative decline within the technology sector, IBM remains the seventh largest technology company by revenue, and 68th largest overall company by revenue in the United States.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] 38 on the 2020 Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2014, IBM was accused of using "financial engineering" to hit its quarterly earnings targets rather than investing for the longer term.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2018, IBM along with 91 additional *Fortune* 500 companies had "paid an effective federal tax rate of 0% or less" as a result of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM Q1 2024 revenue alone was $14.5 billion, up 1% year-over-year.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company's software revenue was up 5% with strong performance in hybrid cloud and AI.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The full FY2024 figure and FY2024 figure and FY2025 quarterly results need updating throughout the article.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company's 15-member board of directors are responsible for overall corporate management and includes the current or former CEOs of Anthem, Dow Chemical, Johnson and Johnson, Royal Dutch Shell, UPS, and Vanguard as well as the president of Cornell University and a retired U.S.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Vanguard Group is the largest shareholder of IBM and as of March 31, 2023, held 15.7% of total shares outstanding.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2011, IBM became the first technology company Warren Buffett's holding company Berkshire Hathaway invested in.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Initially he bought 64 million shares costing $10.5 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Over the years, Buffett increased his IBM holdings, but by the end of 2017 had reduced them by 94.5% to 2.05 million shares; by May 2018, he was completely out of IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM is headquartered in Armonk, New York, a community 37 miles (60 km) north of Midtown Manhattan.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] A nickname for the company is the "**Colossus of Armonk**".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Its principal building, referred to as CHQ, is a 283,000-square-foot (26,300 m2) glass and stone edifice on a 25-acre (10 ha) parcel amid a 432-acre former apple orchard the company purchased in the mid-1950s.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] There are two other IBM buildings within walking distance of CHQ: the North Castle office, which previously served as IBM's headquarters; and the Louis V.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Gerstner, Jr., Center for Learning (formerly known as IBM Learning Center (ILC)), a resort hotel and training center, which has 182 guest rooms, 31 meeting rooms, and various amenities.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM operates in 174 countries as of 2016, with mobility centers in smaller market areas and major campuses in the larger ones.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In New York City, IBM has several offices besides CHQ, including the IBM Watson headquarters at Astor Place in Manhattan.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Outside of New York, major campuses in the United States include Austin, Texas; Research Triangle Park (Raleigh-Durham), North Carolina; Rochester, Minnesota; and Silicon Valley, California.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's real estate holdings are varied and globally diverse.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Towers occupied by IBM include 1250 René-Lévesque (Montreal, Canada) and One Atlantic Center (Atlanta, Georgia, US).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In Beijing, China, IBM occupies Pangu Plaza, the city's seventh tallest building and overlooking Beijing National Stadium ("Bird's Nest"), home to the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM India Private Limited is the Indian subsidiary of IBM, which is headquartered at Bangalore, Karnataka.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] It has facilities in Coimbatore, Chennai, Kochi, Ahmedabad, Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, Pune, Gurugram, Noida, Bhubaneshwar, Surat, Visakhapatnam, Hyderabad, Bangalore and Jamshedpur.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Defunct IBM campuses include the IBM Somers Office Complex (Somers, New York), Spango Valley (Greenock, Scotland), and Tour Descartes (Paris, France).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company's contributions to industrial architecture and design include works by Marcel Breuer, Eero Saarinen, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, I.M.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Van der Rohe's building in Chicago was recognized with the 1990 Honor Award from the National Building Museum.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2004, concerns were raised related to IBM's contribution in its early days to pollution in its original location in Endicott, New York.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM reported its total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 621 kilotons (-324 /-34.3% year-on-year).
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In February 2021, IBM committed to achieve net zero greenhouse gas emissions by the year 2030.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] However, there is no evidence that IBM has actually made any substantial changes to actually do so.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM has a large and diverse portfolio of products and services.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] As of 2016, these offerings fall into the categories of cloud computing, artificial intelligence, commerce, data and analytics, Internet of things (IoT), IT infrastructure, mobile, digital workplace and cybersecurity.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Since 1954, IBM has sold mainframe computers, the latest being the IBM z series.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The most recent model, the IBM z17, was released in 2025.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 1990, IBM released the Power microprocessors, which were designed into many console gaming systems, including Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, and Nintendo's Wii U.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2016, the company launched all-flash arrays designed for small and midsized companies, which includes software for data compression, provisioning, and snapshots across various systems.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In January 2019, IBM introduced its first commercial quantum computer: IBM Q System One.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In March 2020, it was announced that IBM would build Europe's first quantum data center in Ehningen, Germany.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The center, operated by the Fraunhofer Society, was opened in 2024.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Since 2009, IBM has owned SPSS, a software package used for statistical analysis in the social sciences.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM also owned The Weather Company, which provides weather forecasting and includes weather.com and Weather Underground, which was sold in 2024.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM Cloud includes infrastructure as a service (IaaS), software as a service (SaaS) and platform as a service (PaaS) offered through public, private and hybrid cloud delivery models.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] For instance, the IBM Bluemix PaaS enables developers to quickly create complex websites on a pay-as-you-go model.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM SoftLayer is a dedicated server, managed hosting and cloud computing provider, which in 2011 reported hosting more than 81,000 servers for more than 26,000 customers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM also provides Cloud Data Encryption Services (ICDES), using cryptographic splitting to secure customer data.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In May 2022, IBM announced the company had signed a multi-year Strategic Collaboration Agreement with Amazon Web Services to make a wide variety of IBM software available as a service on AWS Marketplace.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Additionally, the deal includes both companies making joint investments that make it easier for companies to consume IBM's offering and integrate them with AWS, including developer training and software development for select markets.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM Watson is a technology platform that uses natural language processing and machine learning to reveal insights from large amounts of unstructured data.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watson was debuted in 2011 on the American game show *Jeopardy!*, where it competed against champions Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter in a three-game tournament and won.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watson has since been applied to business, healthcare, developers, and universities.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] For example, IBM has partnered with Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center to assist with considering treatment options for oncology patients and for doing melanoma screenings.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Several companies use Watson for call centers, either replacing or assisting customer service agents.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM also provides infrastructure for the New York City Police Department through its IBM Cognos Analytics to perform data visualizations of CompStat crime data.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In June 2020, IBM announced that it was exiting the facial recognition business.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In May 2023, IBM revealed Watsonx, a Generative AI toolkit that is powered by IBM's own Granite models with option to use other publicly available LLMs.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watsonx has multiple services for training and fine tuning models based on confidential data.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] A year later, IBM open-sourced Granite code models and put them on Hugging Face for public use.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In October 2024, IBM introduced Granite 3.0, an open-source large language model designed for enterprise AI applications.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] With 160,000 consultants globally as of 2024, IBM is one of the ten largest consulting companies in the world, with capabilities spanning strategy and management consulting, experience design, technology and systems integration, and operations.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's consulting business was valued at $20 billion, as of 2024.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Now, IBM Research constitutes the largest industrial research organization in the world, with 12 labs on 6 continents.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM Research is headquartered at the Thomas J.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In terms of investment, IBM's R&D expenditure totals several billion dollars each year.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2012, that expenditure was approximately $6.9 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Recent allocations have included $1 billion to create a business unit for Watson in 2014, and $3 billion to create a next-gen semiconductor along with $4 billion towards growing the company's "strategic imperatives" (cloud, analytics, mobile, security, social) in 2015.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2024, IBM reported research and development expenditures of $7.48 billion, representing an increase of approximately 10.3% compared to the previous year’s expenditure of $6.78 billion.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM has been a leading proponent of the Open Source Initiative, and began supporting Linux in 1998.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company invests billions of dollars in services and software based on Linux through the IBM Linux Technology Center, which includes over 300 Linux kernel developers.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's open source involvement has not been trouble-free, however (see *SCO v.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Additionally, in 1990 company scientists used a scanning tunneling microscope to arrange 35 individual xenon atoms to spell out the company initialism, marking the first structure assembled one atom at a time.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] A major part of IBM research is the generation of patents.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Since its first patent for a traffic signaling device, IBM has been one of the world's most prolific patent sources.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2021, the company held the record for most patents generated by a business for 29 consecutive years for the achievement.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] As of 2021, IBM holds the record for most annual U.S. patents generated by a business for 29 consecutive years.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In 2001, IBM became the first company to generate more than 3,000 patents in one year, beating this record in 2008 with over 4,000 patents.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM has also been criticized as being a patent troll.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM is nicknamed *Big Blue* partly because of its blue logo and color scheme, and also in reference to its former *de facto* dress code of white shirts with blue suits.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company logo has undergone several changes over the years, with its current "8-bar" logo designed in 1972 by graphic designer Paul Rand.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] It was a general replacement for a 13-bar logo, since period photocopiers did not render narrow (as opposed to tall) stripes well.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Aside from the logo, IBM used Helvetica as a corporate typeface for 50 years, until it was replaced in 2017 by the custom-designed IBM Plex.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM has a valuable brand as a result of over 100 years of operations and marketing campaigns.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] As a result, IBM CEO Ginni Rometty became the third female member of the Master's governing body, the Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM is also a major sponsor in professional tennis, with engagements at the U.S.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Open, Wimbledon, the Australian Open, and the French Open.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company also sponsored the Olympic Games from 1960 to 2000, and the National Football League from 2003 to 2012.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In Japan, IBM employees also have an American football team complete with pro stadium, cheerleaders and televised games, competing in the Japanese X-League as the "Big Blue".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM is among the world's largest employers, with over 297,900 employees worldwide in 2022, with about 160,000 of those being tech consultants.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's leadership programs include Extreme Blue, an internship program, and the IBM Fellow award, offered since 1963 based on technical achievement.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Many IBM employees have achieved notability outside of work and after leaving IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Other former IBM employees include NASA astronaut Michael J.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Massimino, Canadian astronaut and former Governor General Julie Payette, noted musician Dave Matthews, Harvey Mudd College president Maria Klawe, Western Governors University president emeritus Robert Mendenhall, former University of Kentucky president Lee T.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Todd Jr., former University of Iowa president Bruce Harreld, NFL referee Bill Carollo, former Rangers F.C. chairman John McClelland, and recipient of the Nobel Prize in Literature J.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Thomas Watson Jr. also served as the 11th national president of the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Five IBM employees have received the Nobel Prize: Leo Esaki, of the Thomas J.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., in 1973, for work in semiconductors; Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer, of the Zurich Research Center, in 1986, for the scanning tunneling microscope; and Georg Bednorz and Alex Müller, also of Zurich, in 1987, for research in superconductivity.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Six IBM employees have won the Turing Award, including the first female recipient Frances E.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Ten National Medals of Technology and five National Medals of Science have been awarded to IBM employees.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Employees are often referred to as "IBMers" and "Once An IBMer, Always An IBMer.".
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] IBM's culture has evolved significantly over its century of operations.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] In its early days, a dark (or gray) suit, white shirt, and a "sincere" tie constituted the public uniform for IBM employees.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] During IBM's management transformation in the 1990s, CEO Louis V.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Gerstner Jr. relaxed these codes, normalizing the dress and behavior of IBM employees.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] Similar IBM backronyms exist within the industry, such as Computerworld producing a badge labelled "It's Better Manually" implying it would be easier to use a paper-based system than a computer.
[src:pl-i-language/ibm] The company has traditionally resisted labor union organizing, although unions represent some IBM workers outside the United States.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] A mainframe computer is large but not as large as a supercomputer and has more processing power than some other classes of computers, such as minicomputers, workstations, and personal computers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Most large-scale computer-system architectures were established in the 1960s, but they continue to evolve.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframe computers are often used as servers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The term *mainframe* was derived from the large cabinet, called a *main frame*, that housed the central processing unit and main memory of early computers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Later, the term *mainframe* was used to distinguish high-end commercial computers from less powerful machines.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The high stability and reliability of mainframes enable these machines to run uninterrupted for very long periods of time, with mean time between failures (MTBF) measured in decades.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframes have high availability, one of the primary reasons for their longevity, since they are typically used in applications where downtime would be costly or catastrophic.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] High levels of reliability, availability and serviceability (RAS) is a defining characteristic of mainframe computers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In the late 1950s, mainframes had only a rudimentary interactive interface (the console) and used sets of punched cards, paper tape, or magnetic tape to transfer data and programs.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] They operated in batch mode to support back office functions such as payroll and customer billing, most of which were based on repeated tape-based sorting and merging operations followed by line printing to preprinted continuous stationery.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] When interactive user terminals were introduced, they were used almost exclusively for applications (e.g. airline booking) rather than program development.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] However, in 1961 the first academic, general-purpose timesharing system that supported software development, CTSS, was released at MIT on an IBM 709, later 7090 and 7094.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Typewriter and Teletype devices were common control consoles for system operators through the early 1970s, although ultimately supplanted by keyboard/display devices.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] By the early 1970s, many mainframes acquired interactive user terminals operating as timesharing computers, supporting hundreds of users simultaneously along with batch processing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Users gained access through keyboard/typewriter terminals and later character-mode text terminal cathode-ray tube displays with integral keyboards, or finally from personal computers equipped with terminal emulation software.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] By the 1980s, many mainframes supported general purpose graphic display terminals, and terminal emulation, but not graphical user interfaces.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] This form of end-user computing became obsolete in the 1990s due to the advent of personal computers provided with graphical user interfaces.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] After 2000, modern mainframes partially or entirely phased out classic "green screen" and color display terminal access for end-users in favour of Web-style user interfaces.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The infrastructure requirements were drastically reduced during the mid-1990s, when CMOS mainframe designs replaced the older bipolar technology.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM claimed that its newer mainframes reduced data center energy costs for power and cooling, and reduced physical space requirements compared to server farms.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Modern mainframes can run multiple different instances of operating systems at the same time.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] This technique of virtual machines allows applications to run as if they were on physically distinct computers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In this role, a single mainframe can replace higher-functioning hardware services available to conventional servers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] While mainframes pioneered this capability, virtualization is now available on most families of computer systems, though not always to the same degree or level of sophistication.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframes can add or hot swap system capacity without disrupting system function, with specificity and granularity to a level of sophistication not usually available with most server solutions.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Modern mainframes, notably the IBM Z servers, offer two levels of virtualization: logical partitions (LPARs, via the PR/SM facility) and virtual machines (via the z/VM operating system).
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Many mainframe customers run two machines: one in their primary data center and one in their backup data center—fully active, partially active, or on standby—in case there is a catastrophe affecting the first building.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Test, development, training, and production workload for applications and databases can run on a single machine, except for extremely large demands where the capacity of one machine might be limiting.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Such a two-mainframe installation can support continuous business service, avoiding both planned and unplanned outages.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In practice, many customers use multiple mainframes linked either by Parallel Sysplex and shared DASD (in IBM's case), or with shared, geographically dispersed storage provided by EMC or Hitachi.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframes are designed to handle very high volume input and output (I/O) and emphasize throughput computing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Since the late 1950s, mainframe designs have included subsidiary hardware (called *channels* or *peripheral processors*) which manage the I/O devices, leaving the CPU free to deal only with high-speed memory.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] It is common in mainframe shops to deal with massive databases and files.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Gigabyte to terabyte-size record files are not unusual.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Compared to a typical PC, mainframes commonly have hundreds to thousands of times as much data storage online, and can access it reasonably quickly.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Other server families also offload I/O processing and emphasize throughput computing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframe return on investment (ROI), like any other computing platform, is dependent on its ability to scale, support mixed workloads, reduce labor costs, deliver uninterrupted service for critical business applications, and several other risk-adjusted cost factors.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframes also have execution integrity characteristics for fault tolerant computing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] This hardware-level feature, also found in HP's NonStop systems, is known as lock-stepping, because both processors take their "steps" (i.e. instructions) together.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Not all applications absolutely need the assured integrity that these systems provide, but many do, such as financial transaction processing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] A **mainframe audit** is a comprehensive inspection of computer processes, security, and procedures, with recommendations for improvement.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Organizations in different industries have different auditing and security requirements.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Some factors affecting the organizations' requirements are: regulatory requirements and other external factors; management, objectives, and business practices; and the organizations' performance compared to the industry.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] This information can be obtained by conducting outside research, interviewing employees, touring the data center and observing activities, consultations with technical experts, and looking at company manuals and business plans.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Another consideration is the level of mainframe access employees have and if password policies are in place and followed.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Evidence of implementation can be obtained by requesting employee manuals, evaluating the software and user histories, and by physical observation of the environment.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Physical access is also an area of interest.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Are cables adequately protected from damage and sniffing between the Network and the Data Center?
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] This can be achieved by proper routing of the cables, encryption, and a good network topology.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Physical observation of where the cables are routed and confirmation of the security procedures should be obtained.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Tests of controls should be conducted to determine any additional weaknesses.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Does the mainframe have access to an adequate uninterruptible power supply?
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Are physical controls such as power badges for access, fire suppression devices, and locks in place to protect the data center (and the mainframe inside) from theft, manipulation or damage?
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Physical observation is necessary to ensure these requirements.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM, with the IBM Z series, continues to be a major manufacturer in the mainframe market.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In 2000, Hitachi co-developed the zSeries z900 with IBM to share expenses, and the latest Hitachi AP10000 models are made by IBM.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Unisys manufactures ClearPath Libra mainframes, based on earlier Burroughs MCP products and ClearPath Dorado mainframes based on Sperry Univac OS 1100 product lines.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Hewlett Packard Enterprise sells its unique NonStop systems, which it acquired with Tandem Computers and which some analysts classify as mainframes.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Groupe Bull's GCOS, Stratus OpenVOS, Fujitsu (formerly Siemens) BS2000, and Fujitsu-ICL VME mainframes are still available in Europe, and Fujitsu (formerly Amdahl) GS21 mainframes globally.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] NEC with ACOS and Hitachi with AP10000-VOS3 still maintain mainframe businesses in the Japanese market.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The amount of vendor investment in mainframe development varies with market share.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Fujitsu and Hitachi both continue to use custom S/390-compatible processors, as well as other CPUs (including POWER and Xeon) for lower-end systems.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Bull uses a mixture of Itanium and Xeon processors.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] NEC uses Xeon processors for its low-end ACOS-2 line, but develops the custom NOAH-6 processor for its high-end ACOS-4 series.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM also develops custom processors in-house, such as the Telum.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Unisys produces code compatible mainframe systems that range from laptops to cabinet-sized mainframes that use homegrown CPUs as well as Xeon processors.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Furthermore, there exists a market for software applications to manage the performance of mainframe implementations.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In addition to IBM, significant market competitors include BMC and Precisely; former competitors include Compuware and CA Technologies.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Several manufacturers and their successors produced mainframe computers from the 1950s until the early 21st century, with gradually decreasing numbers and a gradual transition to simulation on Intel chips rather than proprietary hardware.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The US group of manufacturers was first known as "IBM and the Seven Dwarfs": usually Burroughs, UNIVAC, NCR, Control Data, Honeywell, General Electric and RCA, although some lists varied.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Later, with the departure of General Electric and RCA, it was referred to as IBM and the BUNCH.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM's dominance grew out of their 700/7000 series and, later, the development of the 360 series mainframes.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The latter architecture has continued to evolve into their current zSeries mainframes which, along with the then Burroughs and Sperry (now Unisys) MCP-based and OS1100 mainframes, are among the few mainframe architectures still extant that can trace their roots to this early period.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] While IBM's zSeries can still run 24-bit System/360 code, the 64-bit IBM Z CMOS servers have nothing physically in common with the older systems.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Notable manufacturers outside the US were Siemens and Telefunken in Germany, ICL in the United Kingdom, Olivetti in Italy, and Fujitsu, Hitachi, Oki, and NEC in Japan.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The Soviet Union and Warsaw Pact countries manufactured close copies of IBM mainframes during the Cold War; the BESM series and Strela are examples of independently designed Soviet computers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Elwro in Poland was another Eastern Bloc manufacturer, producing the ODRA, R-32 and R-34 mainframes.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In 1984, estimated sales of desktop computers ($11.6 billion) exceeded mainframe computers ($11.4 billion) for the first time.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM received the vast majority of mainframe revenue.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] During the 1980s, minicomputer-based systems grew more sophisticated and were able to displace the lower end of the mainframes.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] These computers, sometimes called *departmental computers*, were typified by the Digital Equipment Corporation VAX series.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In 1991, AT&T Corporation briefly owned NCR.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] During the same period, companies found that servers based on microcomputer designs could be deployed at a fraction of the acquisition price and offer local users much greater control over their own systems given the IT policies and practices at that time.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Terminals used for interacting with mainframe systems were gradually replaced by personal computers.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Consequently, demand plummeted and new mainframe installations were restricted mainly to financial services and government.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In the early 1990s, there was a rough consensus among industry analysts that the mainframe was a dying market as mainframe platforms were increasingly replaced by personal computer networks.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] *InfoWorld*'s Stewart Alsop infamously predicted that the last mainframe would be unplugged in 1996; in 1993, he cited Cheryl Currid, a computer industry analyst as saying that the last mainframe "will stop working on December 31, 1999", a reference to the anticipated Year 2000 problem (Y2K).
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] That trend started to turn around in the late 1990s as corporations found new uses for their existing mainframes and as the price of data networking collapsed in most parts of the world, encouraging trends toward more centralized computing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The growth of e-business also dramatically increased the number of back-end transactions processed by mainframe software as well as the size and throughput of databases.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Batch processing, such as billing, became even more important (and larger) with the growth of e-business, and mainframes are particularly adept at large-scale batch computing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Another factor currently increasing mainframe use is the development of the Linux operating system, which arrived on IBM mainframe systems in 1999.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Linux allows users to take advantage of open source software combined with mainframe hardware RAS.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM's quarterly and annual reports in the 2000s usually reported increasing mainframe revenues and capacity shipments.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] However, IBM's mainframe hardware business has not been immune to the recent overall downturn in the server hardware market or to model cycle effects.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] For example, in the 4th quarter of 2009, IBM's System z hardware revenues decreased by 27% year over year.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] But MIPS (millions of instructions per second) shipments increased 4% per year over the past two years.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Alsop had himself photographed in 2000, symbolically eating his own words ("death to the mainframe").
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In 2012, NASA powered down its last mainframe, an IBM System z9.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] As of 2010, while mainframe technology represented less than 3% of IBM's revenues, it "continue[d] to play an outsized role in Big Blue's results".
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] IBM has continued to launch new generations of mainframes: the IBM z13 in 2015, the z14 in 2017, the z15 in 2019, and the z16 in 2022, the latter featuring among other things an "integrated on-chip AI accelerator" and the new Telum microprocessor.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] A supercomputer is a computer at the leading edge of data processing capability, with respect to calculation speed.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Supercomputers are used for scientific and engineering problems (high-performance computing) which crunch numbers and data, while mainframes focus on transaction processing.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] Mainframes and supercomputers cannot always be clearly distinguished; up until the early 1990s, many supercomputers were based on a mainframe architecture with supercomputing extensions.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] An example of such a system is the HITAC S-3800, which was instruction-set compatible with IBM System/370 mainframes, and could run the Hitachi VOS3 operating system (a fork of IBM MVS).
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] The S-3800 therefore can be seen as being both simultaneously a supercomputer and also an IBM-compatible mainframe.
[src:pl-i-language/mainframe-computer] In 2007, an amalgamation of the different technologies and architectures for supercomputers and mainframes has led to a so-called gameframe.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A PL/I American National Standards Institute (ANSI) technical standard, X3.53-1976, was published in 1976.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I's main domains are data processing, numerical computation, scientific computing, and system programming.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It supports recursion, structured programming, linked data structure handling, fixed-point, floating-point, complex, character string handling, and bit string handling.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The language syntax is English-like and suited for describing complex data formats with a wide set of functions available to verify and manipulate them.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In the 1950s and early 1960s, business and scientific users programmed using different programming languages, usually on different computer hardware.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Business users were moving from Autocoders via COMTRAN to COBOL, while scientific users programmed in Fortran, ALGOL, GEORGE, and others.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The IBM System/360 (announced in 1964 and delivered in 1966) was designed as a common machine architecture for both groups of users, superseding all existing IBM architectures.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Similarly, IBM wanted a single programming language for all users.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It hoped that Fortran could be extended to include the features needed by commercial programmers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In October 1963 a committee was formed composed originally of three IBMers from New York and three members of SHARE, the IBM scientific users group, to propose these extensions to Fortran.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Given the constraints of Fortran, they were unable to do this and embarked on the design of a new programming language based loosely on ALGOL labeled **NPL**.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] This acronym conflicted with that of the UK's National Physical Laboratory and was replaced briefly by **MPPL** (MultiPurpose Programming Language) and, in 1965, with **PL/I** (with a Roman numeral "I").
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The first definition appeared in April 1964.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] IBM took NPL as a starting point and completed the design to a level that the first compiler could be written: the NPL definition was incomplete in scope and in detail.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Control of the PL/I language was vested initially in the New York Programming Center and later at the IBM UK Laboratory at Hursley.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The SHARE and GUIDE user groups were involved in extending the language and had a role in IBM's process for controlling the language through their PL/I Projects.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The experience of defining such a large language showed the need for a formal definition of PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A project was set up in 1967 in IBM Laboratory Vienna to make an unambiguous and complete specification.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] This led in turn to one of the first large scale Formal Methods for development, VDM.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Fred Brooks is credited with ensuring PL/I had the CHARACTER data type.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Date and a colleague added relational database extensions based on Edgar Codd's work.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The language was first specified in detail in the manual "PL/I Language Specifications.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] C28-6571", written in New York in 1965, and superseded by "PL/I Language Specifications.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] IBM continued to develop PL/I in the late sixties and early seventies, publishing it in the GY33-6003 manual.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] These manuals were used by the Multics group and other early implementers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The first compiler was delivered in 1966.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The Standard for PL/I was approved in 1976.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The goals for PL/I evolved during the early development of the language.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Competitiveness with COBOL's record handling and report writing was required.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The language's scope of usefulness grew to include system programming and event-driven programming.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] To achieve these goals, PL/I borrowed ideas from contemporary languages while adding substantial new capabilities and casting it with a distinctive concise and readable syntax.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The language is designed to provide sufficient facilities to be able to satisfy the needs of all programmers, regardless of what problems the language is being applied to.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The summary is extracted from the ANSI PL/I Standard and the ANSI PL/I General-Purpose Subset Standard.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A PL/I program consists of a set of procedures, each of which is written as a sequence of statements.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The `%INCLUDE` construct is used to include text from other sources during program translation.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] All of the statement types are summarized here in groupings which give an overview of the language (the Standard uses this organization).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The base, scale, precision and scale factor of the `Picture-for-arithmetic` type is encoded within the `picture-specification`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The mode is specified separately, with the `picture specification` applied to both the real and the imaginary parts.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Values are computed by expressions written using a specific set of operations and builtin functions, most of which may be applied to aggregates as well as to single values, together with user-defined procedures which, likewise, may operate on and return aggregate as well as single values.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The assignment statement assigns values to one or more variables.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A statement is terminated by a semi-colon.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The maximum length of a statement is implementation defined.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A comment may appear anywhere in a program where a space is permitted and is preceded by the characters forward slash, asterisk and is terminated by the characters asterisk, forward slash (i.e.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Statements may have a label-prefix introducing an entry name (`ENTRY` and `PROCEDURE` statements) or label name, and a condition prefix enabling or disabling a computational condition – e.g., `(NOSIZE)`).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Entry and label names may be single identifiers or identifiers followed by a subscript list of constants (as in `L(12,2):A=0;`).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A sequence of statements becomes a *group* when preceded by a `DO` statement and followed by an `END` statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Groups may include nested groups and begin blocks.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The `IF` statement specifies a group or a single statement as the `THEN` part and the `ELSE` part (see the sample program).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The begin *block* (`BEGIN; stmt-list END;`) may contain declarations for names and internal procedures local to the block.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A *procedure* starts with a `PROCEDURE` statement and is terminated syntactically by an `END` statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The body of a procedure is a sequence of blocks, groups, and statements and contains declarations for names and procedures local to the procedure or `EXTERNAL` to the procedure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Current compilers from Micro Focus, and particularly that from IBM implement many extensions over the standardized version of the language.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The IBM extensions are summarised in the Implementation sub-section for the compiler later.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Although there are some extensions common to these compilers the lack of a current standard means that compatibility is not guaranteed.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Language standardization began in April 1966 in Europe with ECMA TC10.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In 1969 ANSI established a "Composite Language Development Committee", nicknamed "Kludge", later renamed X3J1 PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Standardization became a joint effort of ECMA TC/10 and ANSI X3J1.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A subset of the GY33-6003 document was offered to the joint effort by IBM and became the base document for standardization.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The major features omitted from the base document were multitasking and the attributes for program optimization (e.g., `NORMAL` and `ABNORMAL`).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Proposals to change the base document were voted upon by both committees.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In the event that the committees disagreed, the chairs, initially Michael Marcotty of General Motors and C.A.R.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Hoare representing ICL had to resolve the disagreement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In addition to IBM, Honeywell, CDC, Data General, Digital Equipment Corporation, Prime Computer, Burroughs, RCA, and Univac served on X3J1 along with major users Eastman Kodak, MITRE, Union Carbide, Bell Laboratories, and various government and university representatives.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Further development of the language occurred in the standards bodies, with continuing improvements in structured programming and internal consistency, and with the omission of the more obscure or contentious features.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] As language development neared an end, X3J1/TC10 realized that there were a number of problems with a document written in English text.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Discussion of a single item might appear in multiple places which might or might not agree.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It was difficult to determine if there were omissions as well as inconsistencies.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Consequently, David Beech (IBM), Robert Freiburghouse (Honeywell), Milton Barber (CDC), M.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Donald MacLaren (Argonne National Laboratory), Craig Franklin (Data General), Lois Frampton (Digital Equipment Corporation), and editor, D.J.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Andrews of IBM undertook to rewrite the entire document, each producing one or more complete chapters.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The standard is couched as a formal definition using a "PL/I Machine" to specify the semantics.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It was the first programming language standard to be written as a semi-formal definition.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A "PL/I General-Purpose Subset" ("Subset-G") standard was issued by ANSI in 1981 and a revision published in 1987.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The General Purpose subset was widely adopted as the kernel for PL/I implementations.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I was first implemented by IBM, at its Hursley Laboratories in the United Kingdom, as part of the development of System/360.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The first production PL/I compiler was the PL/I F compiler for the OS/360 Operating System, built by John Nash's team at Hursley in the UK: the runtime library team was managed by I.M.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The PL/I F compiler was written entirely in System/360 assembly language.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] OS/360 is a real-memory environment and the compiler was designed for systems with as little as 64 kilobytes of real storage – F being 64 kB in S/360 parlance.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] To fit a large compiler into the 44 kilobytes of memory available on a 64-kilobyte machine, the compiler consists of a control phase and a large number of compiler phases (approaching 100).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The phases are brought into memory from disk, one at a time, to handle particular language features and aspects of compilation.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Each phase makes a single pass over the partially-compiled program, usually held in memory.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Aspects of the language were still being designed as PL/I F was implemented, so some were omitted until later releases.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I RECORD I/O was shipped with PL/I F Release 2.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The list processing functions – Based Variables, Pointers, Areas and Offsets and LOCATE-mode I/O – were first shipped in Release 4.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In a major attempt to speed up PL/I code to compete with Fortran object code, PL/I F Release 5 does substantial program optimization of DO-loops facilitated by the REORDER option on procedures.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A version of PL/I F was released on the TSS/360 timesharing operating system for the System/360 Model 67, adapted at the IBM Mohansic Lab.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The IBM La Gaude Lab in France developed "Language Conversion Programs" to convert Fortran, Cobol, and Algol programs to the PL/I F level of PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The PL/I D compiler, using 16 kilobytes of memory, was developed by IBM Germany for the DOS/360 low end operating system.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It implements a subset of the PL/I language requiring all strings and arrays to have fixed extents, thus simplifying the run-time environment.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Reflecting the underlying operating system, it lacks dynamic storage allocation and the *controlled* storage class.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Compilers were implemented by several groups in the early 1960s.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The Multics project at MIT, one of the first to develop an operating system in a high-level language, used Early PL/I (EPL), a subset dialect of PL/I, as their implementation language in 1964.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] EPL was developed at Bell Labs and MIT by Douglas McIlroy, Robert Morris, and others.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Initially, it was developed using the TMG compiler-compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The influential Multics PL/I compiler [sic "PL/1"] was the source of compiler technology used by a number of manufacturers and software groups.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] EPL was a system programming language and a dialect of PL/I that had some capabilities absent in the original PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The Honeywell PL/I compiler (for Series 60) is an implementation of the full ANSI X3J1 standard.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The PL/I Optimizer and Checkout compilers produced in Hursley support a common level of PL/I language and aimed to replace the PL/I F compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The checkout compiler is a rewrite of PL/I F in BSL, IBM's PL/I-like proprietary implementation language (later PL/S).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The performance objectives set for the compilers are shown in an IBM presentation to the BCS.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The compilers had to produce identical results – the Checkout Compiler is used to debug programs that would then be submitted to the Optimizer.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Given that the compilers had entirely different designs and were handling the full PL/I language this goal was challenging: it was achieved.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] IBM introduced new attributes and syntax including BUILTIN, case statements (SELECT/WHEN/OTHERWISE), loop controls (ITERATE and LEAVE) and null argument lists to disambiguate, e.g., `DATE**()**`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The PL/I optimizing compiler took over from the PL/I F compiler and was IBM's workhorse compiler from the 1970s to the 1990s.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Like PL/I F, it is a multiple pass compiler with a 44 kilobyte design point, but it is an entirely new design.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Unlike the F compiler, it has to perform compile time evaluation of constant expressions using the run-time library, reducing the maximum memory for a compiler phase to 28 kilobytes.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A second-time around design, it succeeded in eliminating the annoyances of PL/I F such as cascading diagnostics.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It was written in S/360 Macro Assembler by a team, led by Tony Burbridge, most of whom had worked on PL/I F.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Macros were defined to automate common compiler services and to shield the compiler writers from the task of managing real-mode storage, allowing the compiler to be moved easily to other memory models.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The gamut of program optimization techniques developed for the contemporary IBM Fortran H compiler were deployed: the Optimizer equaled Fortran execution speeds in the hands of good programmers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Announced with IBM S/370 in 1970, it shipped first for the DOS/360 operating system in August 1971, and shortly afterward for OS/360, and the first virtual memory IBM operating systems DOS/VS, OS/VS1, OS/VS2, and VM/370.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] (The developers were unaware that while they were shoehorning the code into 28 kb sections, IBM Poughkeepsie was finally ready to ship virtual memory support.) It supported the batch programming environments and, under TSO and CMS, it could be run interactively.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] This compiler went through many versions covering all mainframe operating systems including the operating systems of the Japanese plug-compatible machines (PCMs).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The compiler has been superseded by "IBM PL/I for OS/2, AIX, Linux, z/OS" below.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The PL/I checkout compiler, (colloquially "The Checker") announced in August 1970 was designed to speed and improve the debugging of PL/I programs.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The three-pass design cut the time to compile a program to 25% of that taken by the F Compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It can be run from an interactive terminal, converting PL/I programs into an internal format, "H-text".
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] This format is interpreted by the Checkout compiler at run-time, detecting virtually all types of errors.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Pointers are represented in 16 bytes, containing the target address and a description of the referenced item, thus permitting "bad" pointer use to be diagnosed.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In a conversational environment when an error is detected, control is passed to the user who can inspect any variables, introduce debugging statements and edit the source program.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Perhaps the most commercially successful implementation aside from IBM's was Digital Equipment Corporation's VAX-11 PL/I, later known as VAX PL/I, then DEC PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The implementation is "a strict superset of the ANSI X3.4-1981 PL/I General Purpose Subset and provides most of the features of the new ANSI X3.74-1987 PL/I General Purpose Subset", and was first released in 1980.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It originally used a compiler backend named the VAX Code Generator (VCG) created by a team led by Dave Cutler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The front end was designed by Robert Freiburghouse, and was ported to VAX/VMS from Multics.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It runs on VMS on VAX and Alpha, and on Tru64.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] During the 1990s, Digital sold the compiler to UniPrise Systems, who later sold it to a company named Kednos.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Kednos marketed the compiler as Kednos PL/I until October 2016 when the company ceased trading.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, many US and Canadian universities were establishing time-sharing services on campus and needed conversational compiler/interpreters for use in teaching science, mathematics, engineering, and computer science.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Dartmouth was developing BASIC, but PL/I was a popular choice, as it was concise and easy to teach.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] As the IBM offerings were unsuitable, a number of schools built their own subsets of PL/I and their own interactive support.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The Computer Systems Research Group of the University of Toronto produced the **SP/k** compilers which supported a sequence of subsets of PL/I called SP/1, SP/2, SP/3, ..., SP/8 for teaching programming.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Programs that ran without errors under the SP/k compilers produced the same results under other contemporary PL/I compilers such as IBM's PL/I F compiler, IBM's checkout compiler or Cornell University's PL/C compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Grouse at the University of New South Wales, **PLUM** by Marvin Victor Zelkowitz at the University of Maryland, and **PLUTO** from the University of Toronto.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In a major revamp of PL/I, IBM Santa Teresa in California launched an entirely new compiler in 1992.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The initial shipment was for OS/2 and included most ANSI-G features and many new PL/I features.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Subsequent releases provided additional platforms (MVS, VM, OS/390, AIX and Windows), but as of 2021, the only supported platforms are z/OS and AIX.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] IBM continued to add functions to make PL/I fully competitive with other languages (particularly C and C++) in areas where it had been overtaken.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The corresponding "IBM Language Environment" supports inter-operation of PL/I programs with Database and Transaction systems, and with programs written in C, C++, and COBOL, the compiler supports all the data types needed for intercommunication with these languages.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The PL/I design principles were retained and withstood this major extension, comprising several new data types, new statements and statement options, new exception conditions, and new organisations of program source.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The resulting language is a compatible super-set of the PL/I Standard and of the earlier IBM compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] ORDINAL is a new computational data type.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The ordinal facilities are like those in Pascal, e.g., `DEFINE ORDINAL Colour (red, yellow, green, blue, violet);` but in addition the name and internal values are accessible via built-in functions.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Built-in functions provide access to an ordinal value's predecessor and successor.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The `FIRST` and `LAST` type functions provide access to an ordinal set's range.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The DEFINE-statement (see below) allows additional TYPEs to be declared composed from PL/I's built-in attributes.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The `HANDLE(data structure)` locator data type is similar to the POINTER data type, but strongly typed to bind only to a particular data structure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The `=>` operator is used to select a data structure using a handle.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The UNION attribute (equivalent to CELL in early PL/I specifications) permits several scalar variables, arrays, or structures to share the same storage in a unit that occupies the amount of storage needed for the largest alternative.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] New string-handling functions were added – to centre text, to edit using a picture format, and to trim blanks or selected characters from the head or tail of text, `VERIFYR` to `VERIFY` from the right. and `SEARCH` and `TALLY` functions.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Additional parameter descriptors and attributes were added for omitted arguments and variable length argument lists.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The VALUE attribute declares an identifier as a constant (derived from a specific literal value or restricted expression).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Parameters can have the BYADDR (pass by address) or BYVALUE (pass by value) attributes.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The ASSIGNABLE and NONASSIGNABLE attributes prevent unintended assignments.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] `DO FOREVER;` obviates the need for the contrived construct `DO WHILE ( '1'B );`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The DEFINE-statement introduces user-specified names (e.g., INTEGER) for combinations of built-in attributes (e.g., `FIXED BINARY(31,0)`).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Thus `DEFINE ALIAS INTEGER FIXED BINARY(31.0)` creates the TYPE name INTEGER as an alias for the set of built-in attributes FIXED BINARY(31.0).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] `DEFINE STRUCTURE` applies to structures and their members; it provides a TYPE name for a set of structure attributes and corresponding substructure member declarations for use in a structure declaration (a generalisation of the LIKE attribute).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A LEAVE statement to exit a loop, and an ITERATE to continue with the next iteration of a loop.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] UPTHRU and DOWNTHRU options on iterative groups.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The package construct consisting of a set of procedures and declarations for use as a unit.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Variables declared outside of the procedures are local to the package, and can use STATIC, BASED or CONTROLLED storage.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Procedure names used in the package also are local, but can be made external by means of the EXPORTS option of the PACKAGE-statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The RESIGNAL-statement executed in an ON-unit terminates execution of the ON-unit, and raises the condition again in the procedure that called the current one (thus passing control to the corresponding ON-unit for that procedure).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The INVALIDOP condition handles invalid operation codes detected by the PC processor, as well as illegal arithmetic operations such as subtraction of two infinite values.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The ANYCONDITION condition is provided to intercept conditions for which no specific ON-unit has been provided in the current procedure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The STORAGE condition is raised when an ALLOCATE statement is unable to obtain sufficient storage.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] A number of vendors produced compilers to compete with IBM PL/I F or Optimizing compiler on mainframes and minicomputers in the 1970s.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] In the 1980s the target was usually the emerging ANSI-G subset.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I implementations were developed for mainframes from the late 1960s, mini computers in the 1970s, and personal computers in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Although its main use has been on mainframes, there are PL/I compilers for MS-DOS, Windows, OS/2, AIX, OpenVMS, and Unix.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It has been widely used in business data processing and for system use for writing operating systems on certain platforms.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I did not fulfill its supporters' hopes that it would displace Fortran and COBOL and become the major player on mainframes.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It remained a minority but significant player.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] There cannot be a definitive explanation for this, but some trends in the 1970s and 1980s militated against its success by progressively reducing the territory on which PL/I enjoyed a competitive advantage.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] First, the nature of the mainframe software environment changed.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Application subsystems for database and transaction processing (CICS and IMS and Oracle on System 370) and application generators became the focus of mainframe users' application development.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Significant parts of the language became irrelevant because of the need to use the corresponding native features of the subsystems (such as tasking and much of input/output).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Fortran was not used in these application areas, confining PL/I to COBOL's territory; most users stayed with COBOL.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] But as the PC became the dominant environment for program development, Fortran, COBOL and PL/I all became minority languages overtaken by C++, Java and the like.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Second, PL/I was overtaken in the system programming field.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The IBM system programming community was not ready to use PL/I; instead, IBM developed and adopted a proprietary dialect of PL/I for system programming. – PL/S.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] With the success of PL/S inside IBM, and of C outside IBM, the unique PL/I strengths for system programming became less valuable.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Third, the development environments grew capabilities for interactive software development that, again, made the unique PL/I interactive and debugging strengths less valuable.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Fourth, features such as structured programming, character string operations, and object orientation were added to COBOL and Fortran, which further reduced PL/I's relative advantages.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] On mainframes there were substantial business issues at stake too.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] IBM's hardware competitors had little to gain and much to lose from success of PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Compiler development was expensive, and the IBM compiler groups had an in-built competitive advantage.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Many IBM users wished to avoid being locked into proprietary solutions.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] With no early support for PL/I by other vendors it was best to avoid PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] This article uses the PL/I standard as the reference point for language features.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] But a number of features of significance in the early implementations were not in the Standard; and some were offered by non-IBM compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] And the de facto language continued to grow after the standard, ultimately driven by developments on the Personal Computer.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Multithreading, under the name "multitasking", was implemented by PL/I F, the PL/I Checkout and Optimizing compilers, and the newer AIX and Z/OS compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] It comprised the data types EVENT and TASK, the TASK-option on the CALL-statement (Fork), the WAIT-statement (Join), the `DELAY(delay-time)`, EVENT-options on the record I/O statements and the UNLOCK statement to unlock locked records on EXCLUSIVE files.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Event data identify a particular event and indicate whether it is complete ('1'B) or incomplete ('0'B): task data items identify a particular task (or process) and indicate its priority relative to other tasks.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The first IBM *Compile time preprocessor* was built by the IBM Boston Advanced Programming Center located in Cambridge, Mass, and shipped with the PL/I F compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The `%INCLUDE` statement was in the Standard, but the rest of the features were not.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The DEC and Kednos PL/I compilers implemented much the same set of features as IBM, with some additions of their own.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] IBM has continued to add preprocessor features to its compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The preprocessor treats the written source program as a sequence of tokens, copying them to an output source file or acting on them.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] When a % token is encountered the following compile time statement is executed: when an identifier token is encountered and the identifier has been DECLAREd, ACTIVATEd, and assigned a compile time value, the identifier is replaced by this value.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Tokens are added to the output stream if they do not require action (e.g., `+`), as are the values of ACTIVATEd compile time expressions.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Thus a compile time variable PI could be declared, activated, and assigned using `%PI='3.14159265'`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Subsequent occurrences of PI would be replaced by `3.14159265`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The data type supported are `FIXED DECIMAL` integers and CHARACTER strings of varying length with no maximum length.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The feature allowed programmers to use identifiers for constants – e.g., product part numbers or mathematical constants – and was superseded in the standard by named constants for computational data.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Conditional compiling and iterative generation of source code, possible with compile-time facilities, was not supported by the standard.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Several manufacturers implemented these facilities.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Structured programming additions were made to PL/I during standardization but were not accepted into the standard.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] These features were all included in IBM's PL/I Checkout and Optimizing compilers and in DEC PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I F had offered some debug facilities that were not put forward for the standard but were implemented by others – notably the CHECK(variable-list) condition prefix, `CHECK` on-condition and the `SNAP` option.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] The IBM Optimizing and Checkout compilers added additional features appropriate to the conversational mainframe programming environment (e.g., an `ATTENTION` condition).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Several attempts had been made to design a structure member type that could have one of several datatypes (`CELL` in early IBM).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] With the growth of classes in programming theory, approaches to this became possible on a PL/I base – `UNION`, `TYPE` etc. have been added by several compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] PL/I had been conceived in a single-byte character world.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] With support for Japanese and Chinese language becoming essential, and the developments on International Code Pages, the character string concept was expanded to accommodate wide non-ASCII/EBCDIC strings.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Time and date handling were overhauled to deal with the millennium problem, with the introduction of the DATETIME function that returned the date and time in one of about 35 different formats.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p01] Several other date functions deal with conversions to and from days and seconds.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Though the language is easy to learn and use, implementing a PL/I compiler is difficult and time-consuming.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] A language as large as PL/I needed subsets that most vendors could produce and most users master.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This was not resolved until "ANSI G" was published.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The compile time facilities, unique to PL/I, took added implementation effort and additional compiler passes.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] A PL/I compiler was two to four times as large as comparable Fortran or COBOL compilers, and also that much slower—supposedly offset by gains in programmer productivity.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This was anticipated in IBM before the first compilers were written.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Some argue that PL/I is unusually hard to parse.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The PL/I *keywords* are not reserved so programmers can use them as variable or procedure names in programs.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Because the original PL/I(F) compiler attempts *auto-correction* when it encounters a keyword used in an incorrect context, it often assumes it is a variable name.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This leads to "cascading diagnostics", a problem solved by later compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The effort needed to produce good object code was perhaps underestimated during the initial design of the language.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Program optimization (needed to compete with the excellent program optimization carried out by available Fortran compilers) is unusually complex owing to side effects and pervasive problems with aliasing of variables.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Unpredictable modification can occur asynchronously in exception handlers, which may be provided by "ON statements" in (unseen) callers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Together, these make it difficult to reliably predict when a program's variables might be modified at runtime.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] In typical use, however, user-written error handlers (the ON-unit) often do not make assignments to variables.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] In spite of the aforementioned difficulties, IBM produced the PL/I Optimizing Compiler in 1971.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Compiler writers were free to select whether to implement these features.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] An undeclared variable is, by default, declared by first occurrence—thus misspelling might lead to unpredictable results.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This "implicit declaration" is no different from FORTRAN programs.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] For PL/I(F), however, an attribute listing enables the programmer to detect any misspelled or undeclared variable.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Many programmers were slow to move from COBOL or Fortran due to a perceived complexity of the language and immaturity of the PL/I F compiler.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Programmers were sharply divided into scientific programmers (who used Fortran) and business programmers (who used COBOL), with significant tension and even dislike between the groups.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] PL/I syntax borrowed from both COBOL and Fortran syntax.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] So instead of noticing features that would make their job easier, Fortran programmers of the time noticed COBOL syntax and had the opinion that it was a business language, while COBOL programmers noticed Fortran syntax and looked upon it as a scientific language.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Both COBOL and Fortran programmers viewed it as a "bigger" version of their own language, and both were somewhat intimidated by the language and disinclined to adopt it.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Another factor was *pseudo*-similarities to COBOL, Fortran, and ALGOL.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] These were PL/I elements that looked similar to one of those languages, but worked differently in PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Such frustrations left many experienced programmers with a jaundiced view of PL/I, and often an active dislike for the language.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] On the positive side, full support for pointers to all data types (including pointers to structures), recursion, multitasking, string handling, and extensive built-in functions meant PL/I was indeed quite a leap forward compared to the programming languages of its time.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] However, these were not enough to persuade a majority of programmers or shops to switch to PL/I.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The PL/I F compiler's compile time preprocessor was unusual (outside the Lisp world) in using its target language's syntax and semantics (*e.g.* as compared to the C preprocessor's "#" directives).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] PL/I provides several 'storage classes' to indicate how the lifetime of variables' storage is to be managed – `STATIC`, `AUTOMATIC`, `CONTROLLED`, and `BASED`, and `AREA`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] `STATIC` data is allocated and initialized at load-time, as is done in COBOL "working-storage" and early Fortran.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] `AUTOMATIC` is PL/I's default storage class for `INTERNAL` variables, similar to that of other block-structured languages influenced by ALGOL, like the "auto" storage class in the C language, the default storage allocation in Pascal, and "local-storage" in IBM COBOL.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Storage for `AUTOMATIC` variables is allocated upon entry into the procedure, `BEGIN`-block, or `ON`-unit in which they are declared.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The compiler and runtime system allocate memory for a stack frame to contain them and other housekeeping information.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] If a variable is declared with an `INITIAL`-attribute, code to set it to an initial value is executed at this time.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Care is required to manage the use of initialization properly.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Large amounts of code can be executed to initialize variables every time a scope is entered, especially if the variable is an array or structure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Storage for `AUTOMATIC` variables is freed at block exit.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] `STATIC`, `CONTROLLED`, or `BASED` variables are used to retain variables' contents between invocations of a procedure or block.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] `CONTROLLED` storage is managed using a stack, but the pushing and popping of allocations on the stack is managed by the programmer, using `ALLOCATE` and `FREE` statements.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Storage for `BASED` variables is also managed using `ALLOCATE`/`FREE`, but instead of a stack these allocations have independent lifetimes and are addressed through `OFFSET` or `POINTER` variables.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] `BASED` variables can also be used to address arbitrary storage areas by setting the associated `POINTER` variable, for example following a linked list.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The `AREA` attribute is used to declare programmer-defined heaps.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Data can be allocated and freed within a specific area, and the area can be deleted, read, and written as a unit.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] There are several ways of accessing allocated storage through different data declarations.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Some of these are well defined and safe, some can be used safely with careful programming, and some are inherently unsafe or machine dependent.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Passing a variable as an argument to a parameter by reference allows the argument's allocated storage to be referenced using the parameter.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The DEFINED attribute (e.g., `DCL A(10,10), B(2:9,2:9) DEFINED A`) allows part or all of a variable's storage to be used with a different, but consistent, declaration.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The language definition includes a CELL attribute (later renamed UNION) to allow different definitions of data to share the same storage.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This was not supported by many early IBM compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] These usages are safe and machine independent.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Record I/O and list processing produce situations where the programmer needs to fit a declaration to the storage of the next record or item, before knowing what type of data structure it has.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Based variables and pointers are key to such programs.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The data structures must be designed appropriately, typically using fields in a data structure to encode information about its type and size.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The fields can be held in the preceding structure or, with some constraints, in the current one.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Where the encoding is in the preceding structure, the program needs to allocate a based variable with a declaration that matches the current item (using expressions for extents where needed).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Where the type and size information are to be kept in the current structure ("self defining structures") the type-defining fields must be ahead of the type dependent items and in the same place in every version of the data structure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The REFER-option is used for self-defining extents (e.g., string lengths as in `DCL 1 A BASED, 2 N BINARY, 2 B CHAR(LENGTH REFER A.N.)`, etc – where LENGTH is used to allocate instances of the data structure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] For self-defining structures, any typing and REFERred fields are placed ahead of the "real" data.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] If the records in a data set, or the items in a list of data structures, are organised this way they can be handled safely in a machine independent way.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] PL/I implementations do not (except for the PL/I Checkout compiler) keep track of the data structure used when storage is first allocated.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Any BASED declaration can be used with a pointer into the storage to access the storage – inherently unsafe and machine dependent.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] However, this usage has become important for "pointer arithmetic" (typically adding a certain amount to a known address).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This has been a contentious subject in computer science.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] In addition to the problem of wild references and buffer overruns, issues arise due to the alignment and length for data types used with particular machines and compilers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Many cases where pointer arithmetic might be needed involve finding a pointer to an element inside a larger data structure.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The ADDR function computes such pointers, safely and machine independently.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] It relies on pointers being the same length as `FIXED BINARY(31)` integers and aligned on the same boundaries.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] When PL/I was designed, programs only ran in batch mode, with no possible intervention from the programmer at a terminal.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] An exceptional condition such as division by zero would abort the program yielding only a hexadecimal core dump.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] PL/I exception handling, via ON-units, allowed the program to stay in control in the face of hardware or operating system exceptions and to recover debugging information before closing down more gracefully.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] As a program became properly debugged, most of the exception handling could be removed or disabled: this level of control became less important when conversational execution became commonplace.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Computational exception handling is enabled and disabled by condition prefixes on statements, blocks (including ON-units) and procedures. – e.g., `(SIZE, NOSUBSCRIPTRANGE): A(I)=B(I)*C;`.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Operating system exceptions for Input/Output and storage management are always enabled.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The ON-unit is a single statement or BEGIN-block introduced by an ON-statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Executing the ON statement enables the condition specified, e.g., `ON ZERODIVIDE ON`-unit.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] When the exception for this condition occurs and the condition is enabled, the ON-unit for the condition is executed.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] ON-units are inherited down the call chain.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] When a block, procedure or ON-unit is activated, the ON-units established by the invoking activation are inherited by the new activation.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] They may be over-ridden by another ON-statement and can be reestablished by the REVERT-statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The exception can be simulated using the SIGNAL-statement – e.g., to help debug the exception handlers.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The dynamic inheritance principle for ON-units allows a routine to handle the exceptions occurring within the subroutines it uses.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] If no ON-unit is in effect when a condition is raised a standard system action is taken (often this is to raise the ERROR condition).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The system action can be reestablished using the SYSTEM option of the ON-statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] With some conditions it is possible to complete executing an ON-unit and return to the point of interrupt (e.g., the STRINGRANGE, UNDERFLOW, CONVERSION, OVERFLOW, AREA, and FILE conditions) and resume normal execution.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] With other conditions such as `(SUBSCRIPTRANGE)`, the ERROR condition is raised when this is attempted.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] An ON-unit may be terminated with a `GO TO` preventing a return to the point of interrupt, but permitting the program to continue execution elsewhere as determined by the programmer.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] An ON-unit needs to be designed to deal with exceptions that occur in the ON-unit itself.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The `ON ERROR SYSTEM;` statement allows a nested error trap; if an error occurs within an ON-unit, control might pass to the operating system where a system dump might be produced, or, for some computational conditions, continue execution (as mentioned above).
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The PL/I RECORD I/O statements have relatively simple syntax as they do not offer options for the many situations from end-of-file to record transmission errors that can occur when a record is read or written.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Instead, these complexities are handled in the ON-units for the various file conditions.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The same approach was adopted for AREA sub-allocation and the AREA condition.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The existence of exception handling ON-units can have an effect on optimization, because variables can be inspected or altered in ON-units.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Values of variables that might otherwise be kept in registers between statements, may need to be returned to storage between statements.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] This is discussed in the section on Implementation Issues above.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] PL/I has counterparts for COBOL and FORTRAN's specialized GO TO statements.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Syntax for both COBOL and FORTRAN exist for coding two special two types of GO TO, each of which has a target that is not always the same.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] PL/I has statement label variables (with the LABEL attribute), which can store the value of a statement label, and later be used in a GOTO statement.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] The programmer can also create an array of static label constants by subscripting the statement labels.
[src:pl-i-language/pl-i-p02] Statement label variables can be passed to called procedures, and used to return to a different statement in the calling routine.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] A **punched card** (also **punch card**) is a stiff paper-based medium used to store digital information via the presence or absence of holes in predefined positions.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Developed over the 19th to 20th centuries, punched cards were widely used for data processing, the control of automated machines, and computing.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Early applications included controlling weaving looms and recording census data.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Punched cards were widely used in the 20th century, where unit record machines, organized into data processing systems, used punched cards for data input, data output, and data storage.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The IBM 12-row/80-column punched card format came to dominate the industry.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Many early digital computers used punched cards as the primary medium for input of both computer programs and data.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Punched cards were used for decades before being replaced by magnetic-tape data storage.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] While punched cards are now obsolete as a storage medium, as of 2012, some voting machines still used punched cards to record votes.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Punched cards had a significant cultural impact in the 20th century.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Their legacy persists in modern computing, influencing the 80-character line standard still present in some command-line interfaces and programming environments.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The idea of control and data storage via punched holes was developed independently on several occasions in the modern period.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] In most cases there is no evidence that each of the inventors was aware of any other earlier work.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Basile Bouchon developed the control of a loom by punched holes in paper tape in 1725.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The design was improved by his assistant Jean-Baptiste Falcon and by Jacques Vaucanson.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Although these improvements controlled the patterns woven, they still required an assistant to operate the mechanism.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] In 1804, Joseph Marie Jacquard demonstrated a mechanism to automate loom operation.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Multiple punched cards were linked into a chain of any length.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Each card held the instructions for shedding (raising and lowering the warp) and selecting the shuttle for a single pass.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Semyon Korsakov was reputedly the first to propose punched cards in informatics for information store and search.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Korsakov announced his new method and machines in September 1832.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] There is no evidence that he built a practical example.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] In 1881, Jules Carpentier developed a method of recording and playing back performances on a harmonium using punched cards.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The system was called the *Mélographe Répétiteur* and described that "it writes down ordinary music played on the keyboard '*dans le langage de Jacquard*'", that is, as holes punched in a series of cards.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] By 1887, Carpentier had separated the mechanism into the *Melograph* which recorded the player's key presses and the *Melotrope* which played the music.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] At the end of the 1800s Herman Hollerith created a method for recording data on a medium that could then be read by a machine, developing punched-card data-processing technology for the 1890 U.S. census.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] This was inspired in part by Jacquard loom weaving technology and by railway *punch photographs*.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Punch photographs were quick ways for conductors to mark a ticket with a description of the ticket buyer (e.g., short or tall, dark or light hair).
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] They were used to reduce ticket fraud, as conductors could "read" the punched holes to get a basic description of the person to whom the ticket was sold.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Hollerith's tabulating machines read and summarized data stored on punched cards and they began use for government and commercial data processing.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Initially, these electromechanical machines only counted holes, but by the 1920s they had units for carrying out basic arithmetic operations.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Hollerith founded the *Tabulating Machine Company* (1896), which was one of four companies that were amalgamated via stock acquisition to form a fifth company, Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR) in 1911, later renamed International Business Machines Corporation (IBM) in 1924.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Other companies entering the punched-card business included The Tabulator Limited (Britain, 1902), Deutsche Hollerith-Maschinen Gesellschaft mbH (Dehomag) (Germany, 1911), Powers Accounting Machine Company (US, 1911), Remington Rand (US, 1927), and H.W.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] These companies, and others, manufactured and marketed a variety of punched cards and unit record machines for creating, sorting, and tabulating punched cards, even after the development of electronic computers in the 1950s.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Both IBM and Remington Rand tied punched-card purchases to machine leases, a violation of the US 1914 Clayton Antitrust Act.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] In 1932, the US government took both to court on this issue.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] IBM viewed its business as providing a service and that the cards were part of the machine.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] IBM fought all the way to the Supreme Court and lost in 1936; the court ruled that IBM could only set card specifications.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] IBM had 32 presses at work in Endicott, N.Y., printing, cutting and stacking 5 to 10 million punched cards every day." Punched cards were even used as legal documents, such as U.S.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] During World War II punched card equipment was used by the Allies in some of their efforts to decrypt Axis communications.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] See, for example, Central Bureau in Australia.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] At Bletchley Park in England, "some 2 million punched cards a week were being produced, indicating the sheer scale of this part of the operation".
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] In Nazi Germany, punched cards were used for the censuses of various regions and other purposes (see IBM and the Holocaust).
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Punched card technology developed into a powerful tool for business data processing.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] By 1950, punched cards had become ubiquitous in industry and government.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] "Do not fold, spindle or mutilate", a warning that appeared on some punched cards distributed as documents such as checks and utility bills to be returned for processing, became a motto for the post–World War II era.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] In 1956 IBM signed a consent decree requiring, amongst other things, that IBM would by 1962 have no more than one-half of the punched card manufacturing capacity in the United States.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Thomas Watson Jr.'s decision to sign this decree, where IBM saw the punched card provisions as the most significant point, completed the transfer of power to him from Thomas Watson Sr.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The Univac UNITYPER introduced magnetic tape for data entry in the 1950s.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] During the 1960s, the punched card was gradually replaced as the primary means for data storage by magnetic tape, as better, more capable computers became available.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Mohawk Data Sciences introduced a magnetic tape encoder in 1965, a system marketed as a keypunch replacement, which was somewhat successful.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Punched cards were still commonly used for entering both data and computer programs until the mid-1980s, when the combination of lower-cost magnetic-disk storage, and affordable interactive terminals on less expensive minicomputers made punched cards obsolete for these roles as well.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] However, their influence lives on through many standard conventions and file formats.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The terminals that replaced the punched cards, the IBM 3270, for example, displayed 80 columns of text in text mode, for compatibility with existing software.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Some programs still operate on the convention of 80 text columns, although fewer and fewer do, as newer systems employ graphical user interfaces with variable-width type fonts.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The terms *punched card*, *punch card*, and *punchcard* were all commonly used, as were *IBM card* and *Hollerith card* (after Herman Hollerith).
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] IBM used "IBM card" or, later, "punched card" at first mention in its documentation and thereafter simply "card" or "cards".
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Specific formats were often indicated by the number of character positions available, e.g.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] A sequence of cards that is input to or output from some step in an application's processing is called a *card deck* or simply *deck*.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The rectangular, round, or oval bits of paper punched out were called chad (*chads*) or *chips* (in IBM usage).
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Sequential card columns allocated for a specific use, such as names, addresses, multi-digit numbers, etc., are known as a *field*.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The first card of a group of cards, containing fixed or indicative information for that group, is known as a *master card*.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Cards that are not master cards are *detail cards*.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] The Hollerith punched cards used for the 1890 U.S. census were blank.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Following that, cards commonly had printing such that the row and column position of a hole could be easily seen.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Printing could include having fields named and marked by vertical lines, logos, and more.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] "General-purpose" layouts (see, for example, the IBM 5081 below) were also available.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] For applications requiring master cards to be separated from following detail cards, the respective cards had different upper-corner diagonal cuts and thus could be separated by a sorter.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Other cards typically had one upper-corner diagonal cut, so that cards not oriented correctly, or cards with different corner cuts, could be identified.
[src:pl-i-language/punched-card] Herman Hollerith was awarded three patents in 1889 for electromechanical tabulating machines.
